1
00:00:36,486 --> 00:00:37,885
That's right.

2
00:00:38,988 --> 00:00:40,216
New York.

3
00:00:40,990 --> 00:00:42,685
It's 1958.

4
00:00:44,494 --> 00:00:47,156
Anyway, for a few more minutes it is.

5
00:00:48,164 --> 00:00:51,327
Come midnight, it's going to be 1959.

6
00:00:52,102 --> 00:00:54,400
A whole other feeling.

7
00:00:54,471 --> 00:00:55,995
The New Year.

8
00:00:56,840 --> 00:00:58,102
The future.

9
00:00:59,409 --> 00:01:03,368
Old Daddy Earth fixing to start
one more trip around the sun.

10
00:01:04,180 --> 00:01:07,411
Everybody hoping this ride round
be a little more giddy...

11
00:01:08,251 --> 00:01:09,741
...a little more gay.

12
00:01:10,487 --> 00:01:14,014
All over town, champagne corks
is a-popping.

13
00:01:15,024 --> 00:01:19,757
Over in the Waldorf, the big shots is
dancing to the strains of Guy Lombardo.

14
00:01:21,164 --> 00:01:26,192
In Times Square, the little folks is watching
and waiting for that big ball to drop.

15
00:01:27,871 --> 00:01:31,466
They're all trying to catch hold
of one moment of time...

16
00:01:32,075 --> 00:01:33,599
...to be able to say:

17
00:01:33,843 --> 00:01:35,674
"Right now! This is it!

18
00:01:36,546 --> 00:01:37,638
"I got it!"

19
00:01:39,883 --> 00:01:41,942
Of course, by then it'll be past.

20
00:01:42,552 --> 00:01:44,213
But they're all happy...

21
00:01:45,021 --> 00:01:47,080
...everybody having a good time.

22
00:01:48,191 --> 00:01:49,783
Well, almost everybody.

23
00:01:51,127 --> 00:01:54,255
There's a few lost souls
floating around out there.

24
00:01:56,733 --> 00:01:58,928
Now, if y'all ain't from the city...

25
00:01:59,402 --> 00:02:01,962
...we got something here
called "the rat race. "

26
00:02:03,072 --> 00:02:07,236
Got a way of chewing folks up
so that they don't want no celebrating...

27
00:02:07,644 --> 00:02:09,544
...don't want no cheering up.

28
00:02:09,913 --> 00:02:12,245
Don't care nothing about no New Year's.

29
00:02:13,316 --> 00:02:14,544
Out of hope...

30
00:02:14,818 --> 00:02:16,183
...out of rope...

31
00:02:16,319 --> 00:02:17,616
...out of time.

32
00:02:19,322 --> 00:02:21,347
This here is Norville Barnes.

33
00:02:23,259 --> 00:02:25,227
That office he's stepping out of...

34
00:02:25,295 --> 00:02:28,492
...is the office of the president
of Hudsucker Industries.

35
00:02:29,232 --> 00:02:30,597
That's his office.

36
00:02:32,068 --> 00:02:33,695
How'd he get so high?

37
00:02:34,671 --> 00:02:36,730
And why's he feeling so low?

38
00:02:38,508 --> 00:02:40,305
Is he really going to do it?

39
00:02:41,010 --> 00:02:44,309
Is Norville really going
to jelly up the sidewalk?

40
00:02:46,015 --> 00:02:47,448
Well, the future...

41
00:02:47,951 --> 00:02:50,613
...that's something you can
never tell about.

42
00:02:51,788 --> 00:02:53,050
But the past...

43
00:02:55,458 --> 00:02:57,119
...that's another story.

44
00:05:19,535 --> 00:05:22,095
So in the third quarter
we saw no signs of weakening.

45
00:05:22,171 --> 00:05:25,663
We're up 1 8% over last year's
third-quarter gross...

46
00:05:25,875 --> 00:05:28,366
...and that, needless to say,
is a new record.

47
00:05:28,444 --> 00:05:32,938
Our competition continues to flag
and we continue to take up the slack.

48
00:05:33,383 --> 00:05:36,045
Market shares in most divisions
is increasing...

49
00:05:36,119 --> 00:05:39,179
...and we have opened
seven new regional offices.

50
00:05:39,622 --> 00:05:41,112
Our international division...

51
00:05:41,190 --> 00:05:45,422
...is also showing vigorous signs of upward
movement for the last six months...

52
00:05:45,561 --> 00:05:48,792
...and we're looking
at some exciting things in R&D.

53
00:06:28,938 --> 00:06:32,430
Sub-franchising. Don't talk to me
about sub-franchising.

54
00:06:32,608 --> 00:06:34,974
We're making so much money
in sub-franchising...

55
00:06:35,044 --> 00:06:36,671
...it isn't even funny.

56
00:06:36,979 --> 00:06:41,177
Our nominees and assigns continue
to multiply and expand...

57
00:06:41,250 --> 00:06:44,947
...extending our influence nationally
and abroad.

58
00:06:45,088 --> 00:06:47,579
Our owned and operateds are performing...

59
00:06:47,623 --> 00:06:50,854
...far beyond our expectations
both here and abroad.

60
00:06:50,993 --> 00:06:53,587
And the Federal Tax Act of 1958...

61
00:06:53,763 --> 00:06:57,529
...is giving us a swell write-off
on our plant and heavies.

62
00:07:22,892 --> 00:07:26,726
And our last debenture issue
was this year's fastest seller.

63
00:07:27,263 --> 00:07:29,754
So, third quarter and year-to-date...

64
00:07:29,966 --> 00:07:34,062
...we have set a new record in sales,
a new record in gross...

65
00:07:34,137 --> 00:07:36,765
...a new record in pre-tax earnings...

66
00:07:36,973 --> 00:07:39,874
...a new record in after-tax profits...

67
00:07:40,109 --> 00:07:43,044
...and our stock has split twice
in the past year.

68
00:07:43,412 --> 00:07:44,504
In short...

69
00:07:49,252 --> 00:07:50,651
...we're loaded.

70
00:08:43,472 --> 00:08:44,962
Mr. Hudsucker?

71
00:10:30,479 --> 00:10:33,004
It's a pity to waste a whole Monte Cristo.

72
00:10:33,916 --> 00:10:35,474
He could've opened the window.

73
00:10:35,551 --> 00:10:38,418
Waring Hudsucker never did anything
the easy way.

74
00:10:38,988 --> 00:10:42,082
Why? Why did he do it?
Everything was going so well.

75
00:10:42,925 --> 00:10:45,826
What am l, a headshrinker?
Maybe the man was unhappy.

76
00:10:45,995 --> 00:10:47,758
He didn't look unhappy.

77
00:10:47,930 --> 00:10:51,889
-He didn't look rich.
-He was never an easy man to figure out.

78
00:10:52,435 --> 00:10:55,063
He built this company with his bare hands.

79
00:10:55,705 --> 00:10:57,935
Every step he took was a step up...

80
00:10:59,008 --> 00:11:00,873
...except, of course, this last one.

81
00:11:00,943 --> 00:11:02,911
He was a swell fella...

82
00:11:03,713 --> 00:11:07,649
...but when the president, chairman
and owner of 87% of the stock...

83
00:11:07,717 --> 00:11:08,843
...drops...

84
00:11:09,518 --> 00:11:10,610
...44 floors--

85
00:11:10,686 --> 00:11:11,448
45.

86
00:11:11,520 --> 00:11:12,851
Counting the mezzanine.

87
00:11:13,022 --> 00:11:15,786
Then the company, too, has a problem.
Stillson!

88
00:11:18,060 --> 00:11:20,620
What exactly is the disposition
of Waring's stock?

89
00:11:20,796 --> 00:11:22,127
As you know...

90
00:11:22,198 --> 00:11:24,462
...Hud left no will and no family.

91
00:11:24,533 --> 00:11:27,627
The company bylaws are quite clear
in that event.

92
00:11:27,703 --> 00:11:31,139
"His entire portfolio will be converted
into common stock...

93
00:11:31,307 --> 00:11:35,641
"...and will be sold over the counter
as of the first of the fiscal year...

94
00:11:35,745 --> 00:11:37,838
-"...following his demise."
-Meaning?

95
00:11:38,214 --> 00:11:41,911
Meaning simply that Waring's stock
and control of the company...

96
00:11:42,017 --> 00:11:45,145
...will be made available
to the public January 1st.

97
00:11:46,889 --> 00:11:48,379
Do you mean to say...

98
00:11:48,557 --> 00:11:52,152
...that any slob in a smelly T-shirt
will be able to buy Hudsucker stock?

99
00:11:52,495 --> 00:11:54,588
The company bylaws are quite clear.

100
00:11:54,663 --> 00:11:56,688
My God! You're animals!

101
00:11:56,766 --> 00:12:01,032
How can you discuss his stock
when the man has just leapt 45 floors?

102
00:12:01,103 --> 00:12:01,967
44.

103
00:12:02,037 --> 00:12:03,664
Not counting the mezzanine.

104
00:12:03,739 --> 00:12:04,899
Quit showboating.

105
00:12:04,974 --> 00:12:07,408
The man is gone. The question now
is whether we'll let...

106
00:12:07,476 --> 00:12:10,502
...John Q. Public waltz in here
and buy our company.

107
00:12:10,579 --> 00:12:12,638
What are you suggesting?

108
00:12:12,715 --> 00:12:15,707
Certainly we can't afford
to buy a controlling interest.

109
00:12:15,985 --> 00:12:18,078
Not while the stock is this strong.

110
00:12:19,088 --> 00:12:21,522
How soon before Hud's paper
hits the market?

111
00:12:21,590 --> 00:12:22,420
January 1st.

112
00:12:22,491 --> 00:12:23,890
-Thirty days.
-Four weeks.

113
00:12:23,959 --> 00:12:25,927
-A month at the most.
-One month...

114
00:12:26,028 --> 00:12:28,292
...to make the blue-chip investment
of the century...

115
00:12:28,364 --> 00:12:30,594
...Iook like a round-trip ticket
on the Titanic.

116
00:12:30,666 --> 00:12:33,396
We play up the fact that Hud is dead.

117
00:12:33,502 --> 00:12:34,992
Long live the Hud!

118
00:12:35,037 --> 00:12:36,129
We depress the stock.

119
00:12:36,205 --> 00:12:38,935
-To the point where we can buy 50%.
-51%.

120
00:12:39,008 --> 00:12:40,373
Not counting the mezzanine.

121
00:12:40,443 --> 00:12:41,410
It could work.

122
00:12:41,477 --> 00:12:42,967
-lt should work.
-lt would work.

123
00:12:43,012 --> 00:12:44,707
It's working already.

124
00:12:45,915 --> 00:12:48,884
Waring Hudsucker is abstract art
on Madison Avenue.

125
00:12:50,052 --> 00:12:54,455
What we need now is a new president
who will inspire panic in the stockholder.

126
00:12:54,623 --> 00:12:56,056
-A puppet!
-A proxy!

127
00:12:56,125 --> 00:12:57,114
A pawn!

128
00:12:59,628 --> 00:13:00,754
Some jerk...

129
00:13:01,397 --> 00:13:03,262
...we can really push around.

130
00:13:05,234 --> 00:13:08,965
You punch in at 8:30 every a.m.,
at 7:30 a.m. following a business holiday...

131
00:13:09,038 --> 00:13:11,131
...unless it's a Monday, then it's 8:00.

132
00:13:11,207 --> 00:13:14,802
-Punch in late and they dock you.
-This goes to seven! Urgent.

133
00:13:14,877 --> 00:13:18,574
Incoming articles get a voucher.
Outgoing articles provide a voucher.

134
00:13:18,647 --> 00:13:21,081
Move any article without a voucher,
they dock you!

135
00:13:21,150 --> 00:13:23,584
Take this up to the secretarial pool
on three! ASAP!

136
00:13:23,652 --> 00:13:26,314
Letter-size, a green voucher!
Folder-size, a yellow voucher!

137
00:13:26,388 --> 00:13:27,980
Parcel-size, a maroon voucher!

138
00:13:28,057 --> 00:13:30,116
This is for Morgatross! Chop-chop!

139
00:13:30,192 --> 00:13:32,422
Wrong color voucher and they dock you!

140
00:13:33,295 --> 00:13:35,786
6-7-8-7-0-4-9-Alpha-6!

141
00:13:36,065 --> 00:13:39,193
That is your employee number!
It will not be repeated!

142
00:13:39,401 --> 00:13:41,892
Without it, you can't cash your paycheck.

143
00:13:41,971 --> 00:13:43,700
All right! This goes up to 27!

144
00:13:43,772 --> 00:13:46,741
Return a waiver!
Do not return without a signed waiver!

145
00:13:46,809 --> 00:13:50,939
Inter-office mail is code 37!
Intra-office mail is 37-3.

146
00:13:51,113 --> 00:13:53,377
Outside mail is 3-37.

147
00:13:53,516 --> 00:13:55,313
Code it wrong and they dock you!

148
00:13:55,384 --> 00:13:58,251
I was supposed to have this on 28
ten minutes ago!

149
00:13:58,587 --> 00:14:03,183
This has been your orientation.
Is there anything you do not understand?

150
00:14:03,392 --> 00:14:06,884
If you have not been fully orientated,
you must file a complaint!

151
00:14:06,962 --> 00:14:09,931
File a faulty complaint, and they dock you!

152
00:14:15,471 --> 00:14:16,460
Kloppitt.

153
00:14:16,639 --> 00:14:19,540
Kloppitt, Kloppitt, Kloppitt, Kloppitt....

154
00:14:19,608 --> 00:14:21,098
Max Kloppitt.

155
00:14:21,143 --> 00:14:23,373
"Max Kloppitt, Jr."

156
00:14:31,987 --> 00:14:35,218
What do you do when the envelope
is too big for the slot?

157
00:14:36,559 --> 00:14:38,823
If you fold them, they fire you.

158
00:14:41,030 --> 00:14:42,588
I usually throw them out.

159
00:14:49,171 --> 00:14:50,661
Just got hired today.

160
00:14:51,173 --> 00:14:52,071
Terrific.

161
00:14:52,875 --> 00:14:53,864
Entry level.

162
00:14:57,012 --> 00:14:58,001
But...

163
00:14:58,681 --> 00:15:00,114
...I got big ideas.

164
00:15:00,816 --> 00:15:02,147
I'm sure you do.

165
00:15:02,651 --> 00:15:03,845
For instance...

166
00:15:05,020 --> 00:15:06,248
...Iook at this sweet baby.

167
00:15:10,192 --> 00:15:11,682
I developed it myself.

168
00:15:11,760 --> 00:15:14,194
Yes, sirree, this is my ticket upstairs.

169
00:15:17,866 --> 00:15:19,299
You know, for kids.

170
00:15:20,269 --> 00:15:21,258
Terrific.

171
00:15:22,371 --> 00:15:25,363
So, you see. I won't be working
in the mail room long.

172
00:15:25,441 --> 00:15:27,375
No, I don't guess you will be.

173
00:15:28,611 --> 00:15:30,203
How long've you been here?

174
00:15:30,279 --> 00:15:31,541
Forty-eight years.

175
00:15:32,047 --> 00:15:34,379
Next year they move me up to parcels...

176
00:15:35,484 --> 00:15:36,815
...if I'm lucky.

177
00:15:39,054 --> 00:15:40,954
Attention Hudsucker employees:

178
00:15:41,390 --> 00:15:45,190
We regretfully announce
that at 30 seconds after the hour of noon...

179
00:15:45,294 --> 00:15:46,556
...Hudsucker time...

180
00:15:46,629 --> 00:15:49,291
...Waring Hudsucker, Founder, President...

181
00:15:49,565 --> 00:15:52,500
...and Chairman of the Board
of Hudsucker Industries...

182
00:15:52,568 --> 00:15:54,058
...merged with the infinite.

183
00:15:54,370 --> 00:15:56,861
To mark this occasion of corporate loss...

184
00:15:56,905 --> 00:16:01,035
...we ask that all employees observe
a moment of silent contemplation.

185
00:16:08,150 --> 00:16:10,141
Thank you for your kind attention.

186
00:16:10,319 --> 00:16:13,345
This moment has been duly noted
on your timecards...

187
00:16:13,455 --> 00:16:16,686
...and will be deducted from your pay.
That is all.

188
00:16:20,029 --> 00:16:21,257
Blue letter!

189
00:16:21,430 --> 00:16:22,590
Blue letter!

190
00:16:22,665 --> 00:16:24,428
They're bringing a blue letter!

191
00:16:58,567 --> 00:17:00,000
It's a blue letter.

192
00:17:00,803 --> 00:17:02,065
Top, top level.

193
00:17:02,771 --> 00:17:05,205
Confidential communication
between the brass.

194
00:17:06,175 --> 00:17:07,574
Usually bad news.

195
00:17:08,477 --> 00:17:10,377
They hate blue letters upstairs.

196
00:17:14,583 --> 00:17:15,607
Hate them.

197
00:17:15,684 --> 00:17:16,514
You!

198
00:17:17,052 --> 00:17:18,485
Yeah, you! Barnes!

199
00:17:19,054 --> 00:17:20,316
You don't look busy!

200
00:17:20,889 --> 00:17:22,948
Think you can handle a blue letter?

201
00:17:23,025 --> 00:17:27,655
This letter was sent this morning
by the big man himself, Waring Hudsucker!

202
00:17:27,896 --> 00:17:31,491
It's addressed to Sid Mussburger,
Hudsucker's right-hand man!

203
00:17:31,667 --> 00:17:33,157
It's a blue letter!

204
00:17:33,602 --> 00:17:36,594
That means you got to put it right
in Mussburger's hands.

205
00:17:36,739 --> 00:17:39,037
No secretaries! No receptionists!

206
00:17:39,274 --> 00:17:41,504
No colleagues! No excuses!

207
00:17:42,478 --> 00:17:43,672
Mussburger!

208
00:17:45,581 --> 00:17:49,745
Hi! My name's Buzz, I got the fuzz,
I make the elevator do what she does.

209
00:17:50,552 --> 00:17:51,746
Hang it up to dry.

210
00:17:51,854 --> 00:17:53,754
-What's your pleasure?
-Fourty-four.

211
00:17:53,922 --> 00:17:56,857
Forty-four, the top-brass floor.
Say, buddy...

212
00:17:57,025 --> 00:18:00,791
...what takes 50 years to get to
the top floor and 30 seconds to get down?

213
00:18:01,029 --> 00:18:03,293
Waring Hudsucker! You get it, buddy?

214
00:18:03,632 --> 00:18:06,965
Say, buddy! Mr. Kline, up to nine.
Mrs. Dell, Personnel.

215
00:18:07,069 --> 00:18:09,037
-Mr. Levin, 37.
-Thirty-six.

216
00:18:09,104 --> 00:18:10,196
Walk down!

217
00:18:10,272 --> 00:18:12,035
Ladies and gentlemen,
please step to the rear.

218
00:18:12,107 --> 00:18:14,200
Here comes the gargantuan Mr. Grier.

219
00:18:16,578 --> 00:18:19,877
Buddy, who's the most liquid businessman
on the street?

220
00:18:19,948 --> 00:18:21,279
Waring Hudsucker.

221
00:18:21,950 --> 00:18:25,579
When is the sidewalk fully dressed?
When it's wearing Hudsucker!

222
00:18:26,855 --> 00:18:27,822
You get it?

223
00:18:27,890 --> 00:18:31,348
It's a pun, a knee-slapper,
a play on Jesus, Joseph and Mary....

224
00:18:31,460 --> 00:18:32,950
Is that a blue letter?

225
00:18:32,995 --> 00:18:37,159
Why didn't you tell a guy? Hold on, folks,
we're express to the top floor!

226
00:18:52,548 --> 00:18:53,879
Good luck, buddy.

227
00:18:57,219 --> 00:18:58,481
You'll need it.

228
00:19:11,433 --> 00:19:13,094
Mr. Mussburger's office?

229
00:20:10,459 --> 00:20:11,483
Hello.

230
00:20:12,461 --> 00:20:14,793
Do you have an appointment?

231
00:20:16,465 --> 00:20:18,490
Shall we look in the book?

232
00:20:20,736 --> 00:20:23,569
-We don't seem to be in the book.
-I wouldn't be.

233
00:20:23,739 --> 00:20:27,368
If we had an appointment,
we'd be in the book.

234
00:20:27,943 --> 00:20:29,137
I have this....

235
00:20:29,711 --> 00:20:30,973
Oh, here it is.

236
00:20:36,752 --> 00:20:37,741
Gambotz?

237
00:20:38,654 --> 00:20:39,882
Harry Gambotz?

238
00:20:40,088 --> 00:20:42,682
No, too risky.
He's green but he's not slow.

239
00:20:44,226 --> 00:20:45,284
Who is he?

240
00:20:45,594 --> 00:20:48,495
No, I want an imbecile,
not a cipher, or you'd have the job.

241
00:20:50,933 --> 00:20:52,764
They moved him to grommets and O-rings.

242
00:20:52,834 --> 00:20:54,233
He's doing pretty well.

243
00:20:55,604 --> 00:20:57,299
No, not McClanahan.

244
00:20:58,273 --> 00:21:01,333
He bungled the Teleyard merger
so he's got something to prove.

245
00:21:01,643 --> 00:21:02,905
Who let you in?

246
00:21:03,612 --> 00:21:06,672
Atwater? Tremendous.
Except I just fired him last week.

247
00:21:07,382 --> 00:21:08,542
Mr. Mussburger...

248
00:21:08,650 --> 00:21:10,641
...Mr. Bumstead's waiting downstairs.

249
00:21:10,752 --> 00:21:12,947
-I'll be right there.
-Yes, Mr. Mussburger.

250
00:21:13,021 --> 00:21:14,147
Spit it out!

251
00:21:16,191 --> 00:21:18,625
Maybe you're
the company's biggest moron.

252
00:21:18,894 --> 00:21:22,523
We can't use Morris. Been here too long.
He's a nice guy with too many friends.

253
00:21:22,597 --> 00:21:25,623
In fact, why don't you fire him?
Scratch that, I'll fire him.

254
00:21:26,201 --> 00:21:27,691
Make it fast. Fast!

255
00:21:28,203 --> 00:21:30,171
Mr. Bumstead is growing restless.

256
00:21:30,238 --> 00:21:32,729
Tell him I'll be right there.
Give him a magazine.

257
00:21:32,774 --> 00:21:34,264
What are you, a mute?

258
00:21:36,011 --> 00:21:37,342
How's the stock?

259
00:21:37,446 --> 00:21:39,539
Bad? Well, it's not bad enough.

260
00:21:40,215 --> 00:21:41,375
Listen, chump.

261
00:21:41,450 --> 00:21:45,648
Either you find me a ding-dong or tender
your key to the executive washroom.

262
00:21:45,754 --> 00:21:48,587
That goes double for you, pal.
Earclay? Oodgay!

263
00:21:53,328 --> 00:21:55,728
This better be good. I'm in a bad mood.

264
00:21:56,832 --> 00:22:00,290
Sir, I've got something for you
from the mail room, but first...

265
00:22:00,369 --> 00:22:05,397
...if I could take a minute of your very
valuable time to show you something...

266
00:22:05,474 --> 00:22:08,568
...I've been working on
for the past two or three years.

267
00:22:15,951 --> 00:22:17,384
You know, for kids.

268
00:22:18,253 --> 00:22:21,188
It's perfect for Hudsucker,
not that I'm any great genius.

269
00:22:21,256 --> 00:22:25,420
They say inspiration is 99% perspiration
and in my case it's at least twice that...

270
00:22:25,494 --> 00:22:28,520
-...but I've got to tell you, sir--
-Wait a minute!

271
00:23:13,075 --> 00:23:14,303
Sit down, son.

272
00:23:17,212 --> 00:23:18,201
Go ahead.

273
00:23:20,148 --> 00:23:21,206
Try it on.

274
00:23:34,763 --> 00:23:36,094
Put your feet up.

275
00:23:40,035 --> 00:23:41,024
Go ahead.

276
00:23:43,238 --> 00:23:45,672
Let's get to know one another, shall we?

277
00:23:47,609 --> 00:23:48,803
Let's chat...

278
00:23:52,180 --> 00:23:53,204
...man-to-man.

279
00:24:00,522 --> 00:24:02,854
You're from the basement, aren't you?

280
00:24:04,059 --> 00:24:06,084
And weren't blessed with much...

281
00:24:08,296 --> 00:24:09,490
...education?

282
00:24:09,898 --> 00:24:12,196
Well, I am a college graduate.

283
00:24:12,701 --> 00:24:15,261
But you did not excel in your studies.

284
00:24:15,370 --> 00:24:17,270
Well, I made the dean's list...

285
00:24:18,340 --> 00:24:20,865
...at the Muncie College
of Business Administration.

286
00:24:22,277 --> 00:24:25,041
And your friends called you "jerk,"
didn't they?

287
00:24:26,648 --> 00:24:27,637
"Dope?"

288
00:24:27,749 --> 00:24:28,647
"Dipstick?"

289
00:24:28,717 --> 00:24:30,207
"Lamebrain?" "Schmo?"

290
00:24:30,285 --> 00:24:31,547
Not even behind your back?

291
00:24:31,620 --> 00:24:34,214
They voted me "Most Likely to Succeed."

292
00:24:34,289 --> 00:24:35,483
You're fired.

293
00:24:37,759 --> 00:24:41,092
Get your feet off my desk,
get out of my office.

294
00:24:41,663 --> 00:24:43,324
Leave your apron in the locker room.

295
00:24:43,899 --> 00:24:44,888
Oh, my God!

296
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:49,403
The Bumstead contracts. I've been
working on that deal for four years!

297
00:24:49,571 --> 00:24:51,664
Get out of here! I'll take care of it!

298
00:24:52,507 --> 00:24:55,738
You could have destroyed
the most sensitive document of my career.

299
00:24:55,810 --> 00:24:58,335
Mr. Bumstead is threatening to leave.

300
00:24:58,446 --> 00:24:59,777
I'm on my way down.

301
00:24:59,848 --> 00:25:03,340
We need the first page of the contract
retyped with copies going to Legal.

302
00:25:03,418 --> 00:25:04,976
Yes, Mr. Mussburger.

303
00:25:08,890 --> 00:25:10,414
Out! Out of the office!

304
00:25:13,228 --> 00:25:14,422
Down three points?

305
00:25:14,496 --> 00:25:16,930
That's encouraging. How about New York?

306
00:25:18,099 --> 00:25:19,930
Not that way, through the door!

307
00:25:20,602 --> 00:25:23,332
It'll take three hours to retype
the Bumstead contracts.

308
00:25:23,405 --> 00:25:24,531
Where are you going?

309
00:25:24,606 --> 00:25:26,301
Get out! Stop that!

310
00:25:26,608 --> 00:25:28,200
Mr. Bumstead's threatening to leave.

311
00:25:28,276 --> 00:25:30,801
Not the whole contract, just the first page.

312
00:25:31,112 --> 00:25:33,171
I'll be there. Give him another magazine.

313
00:25:33,248 --> 00:25:35,910
-He says he'll leave.
-I said I'll be there!

314
00:25:37,018 --> 00:25:40,613
Up on your feet! We don't crawl here
at Hudsucker lndustries!

315
00:25:41,022 --> 00:25:42,853
-My leg is on fire!
-No assumptions!

316
00:25:42,924 --> 00:25:46,621
It's early yet. Just let me know
where we stand at the closing bell.

317
00:25:56,071 --> 00:25:58,301
Oh, my God, the Bumstead contracts!

318
00:26:03,745 --> 00:26:05,736
No magazines! No coffee!

319
00:26:05,914 --> 00:26:10,476
Mussburger! I want to see Mussburger!
Or did he jump out a window too?

320
00:26:11,553 --> 00:26:15,182
Don't worry, Mr. Mussburger, I got you!
I got you by your pants.

321
00:26:18,093 --> 00:26:19,025
Pants?

322
00:26:23,598 --> 00:26:27,534
Mr. Mussburger, I'm gonna give
your pants a nice double stitch.

323
00:26:28,003 --> 00:26:31,734
It'll make them real strong
and you're going to look real sharp.

324
00:26:32,607 --> 00:26:35,132
No. Single stitch is fine.

325
00:26:35,343 --> 00:26:37,675
But the double stitch lasts forever.

326
00:26:38,880 --> 00:26:41,474
Why on earth would I want
a double stitch?

327
00:26:42,751 --> 00:26:44,241
To pad your account.

328
00:26:44,619 --> 00:26:46,177
Single stitch is fine.

329
00:26:52,527 --> 00:26:53,619
Damn!

330
00:27:00,235 --> 00:27:03,568
What the heck! Mr. Mussburger
is such a nice man...

331
00:27:03,938 --> 00:27:06,532
...I'm going to give him
a double stitch anyway.

332
00:27:07,642 --> 00:27:10,975
That's some strong stitch, you bet!

333
00:28:57,385 --> 00:28:59,512
"The Einstein of Enterprise."

334
00:29:00,555 --> 00:29:02,045
"The Edison of lndustry."

335
00:29:03,324 --> 00:29:05,485
"The Billion-Dollar Cranium! "

336
00:29:07,362 --> 00:29:08,920
"ldea Man! "

337
00:29:10,765 --> 00:29:13,097
And not one of you has given me
a story on him!

338
00:29:13,168 --> 00:29:14,897
Bunch of lamebrains!

339
00:29:15,370 --> 00:29:18,032
Facts, figures, charts.
They never sold a newspaper!

340
00:29:18,206 --> 00:29:20,174
I read this morning's Argus
and let me tell you something:

341
00:29:20,241 --> 00:29:21,833
I'd wrap a fish in it!

342
00:29:21,910 --> 00:29:23,537
I'd use it as kindling!

343
00:29:23,611 --> 00:29:28,014
I'd train my poodle on it if he wasn't
a French poodle and partial to Paris Soir.

344
00:29:28,183 --> 00:29:31,050
But I wouldn't pay a nickel
to read the thing!

345
00:29:31,119 --> 00:29:33,178
Come on, Chief, give us a break.

346
00:29:33,788 --> 00:29:35,881
Sure, Tibbs. Take a break.

347
00:29:36,658 --> 00:29:38,785
Go to Florida. Lie in the sun.

348
00:29:39,394 --> 00:29:41,885
Wait for a coconut to drop.
File a story on it.

349
00:29:42,197 --> 00:29:45,496
It'd be more of a grabber than your piece
on the county grain surplus!

350
00:29:45,567 --> 00:29:48,058
The human angle!
That's what sells papers!

351
00:29:48,436 --> 00:29:51,894
We need a front page with a heart
and the ldea Man can put it there!

352
00:29:51,973 --> 00:29:53,463
If we had more access--

353
00:29:53,508 --> 00:29:55,999
If a frog had wings
it wouldn't bump it's ass hopping.

354
00:29:56,077 --> 00:29:58,136
I don't want excuses, I want results!

355
00:29:58,546 --> 00:30:01,208
What makes the ldea Man tick?
Where's he from?

356
00:30:01,316 --> 00:30:04,911
I want to know everything about him!
Has he got a girl? Has he got parents?

357
00:30:04,986 --> 00:30:07,045
Everybody has parents.

358
00:30:07,222 --> 00:30:08,883
All right, how many?

359
00:30:10,024 --> 00:30:12,254
How about it, Parkinson?
You've been awfully quiet.

360
00:30:14,229 --> 00:30:15,662
Still waters run deep.

361
00:30:15,763 --> 00:30:18,254
Only thing deep with Parkinson
are the holes in his ears.

362
00:30:18,333 --> 00:30:19,960
Yes! Idea Man!

363
00:30:20,602 --> 00:30:23,833
What are his hopes and dreams,
his desires and aspirations?

364
00:30:24,138 --> 00:30:26,834
Does he think all the time
or a certain portion of the day?

365
00:30:26,908 --> 00:30:30,469
How tall is he? Where does he sleep?
What does he have for breakfast?

366
00:30:30,545 --> 00:30:32,775
Does he put jam on his toast
or doesn't he?

367
00:30:32,847 --> 00:30:34,906
If not, why not and since when?

368
00:30:35,917 --> 00:30:36,906
Well?

369
00:30:38,253 --> 00:30:39,777
You're useless.

370
00:30:40,522 --> 00:30:41,784
Yes. Idea Man.

371
00:30:42,457 --> 00:30:43,446
"Creator."

372
00:30:43,525 --> 00:30:44,583
"lnnovator."

373
00:30:44,859 --> 00:30:46,190
"Cerebrator."

374
00:30:46,861 --> 00:30:47,919
Fake!

375
00:30:48,563 --> 00:30:50,588
I tell you, the guy's a phony.

376
00:30:50,665 --> 00:30:52,189
-Phony?
-As a $3 bill.

377
00:30:52,267 --> 00:30:53,928
-Says who?
-Says me, Amy Archer!

378
00:30:54,002 --> 00:30:56,334
Why is he an ldea Man?
Because Hudsucker says so?

379
00:30:56,404 --> 00:30:59,032
What are his ideas?
Why can't anyone interview him?

380
00:30:59,107 --> 00:31:01,200
Five bucks says she mentions her Pulitzer.

381
00:31:02,043 --> 00:31:04,034
Again? You're on.

382
00:31:04,112 --> 00:31:06,046
Look at the mug on this guy.

383
00:31:06,114 --> 00:31:09,277
The jutting eyebrows, the simian forehead,
the idiotic grin.

384
00:31:09,350 --> 00:31:11,250
He has a face only a mother could love...

385
00:31:12,654 --> 00:31:13,643
...on payday.

386
00:31:13,888 --> 00:31:16,857
The only story here is
how this guy made a monkey out of you.

387
00:31:16,925 --> 00:31:19,553
Like it or not, I'm still editor of this rag.

388
00:31:19,727 --> 00:31:22,821
I thought you were writing,
"J. Edgar Hoover: When Will He Marry?"

389
00:31:22,897 --> 00:31:26,128
-I filed it yesterday. Nice tie, Earl.
-Well, do a follow-up.

390
00:31:26,267 --> 00:31:28,292
"Hoover: Crimebuster or Pantywaist?"

391
00:31:28,369 --> 00:31:31,600
The rest of you mugs get some brains
and get me that ldea Man story!

392
00:31:33,241 --> 00:31:34,469
He's the bunk.

393
00:31:40,582 --> 00:31:42,447
I'll stake my Pulitzer on it!

394
00:31:44,986 --> 00:31:47,011
Say, buddy, where'd you get the new duds?

395
00:31:47,088 --> 00:31:50,023
Say, buddy, how did Old Bucketbutt
like his blue letter?

396
00:31:50,592 --> 00:31:53,755
Did he bust a gut? Did he die?
Well, hello, Mr. Mussburger.

397
00:31:53,828 --> 00:31:55,261
Lobby, we haven't got all day.

398
00:31:55,330 --> 00:31:57,093
Right away, Mr. Mussburger.

399
00:31:57,231 --> 00:31:59,290
How're you this fine morning, sir?

400
00:32:00,068 --> 00:32:02,434
It's been a pleasure serving you today, sir.

401
00:32:02,503 --> 00:32:05,165
It's been a pleasure serving you too, buddy.

402
00:32:05,340 --> 00:32:09,037
Shouldn't we be a little concerned
with the downward spiral of our stock...

403
00:32:09,110 --> 00:32:10,475
...these past few days?

404
00:32:10,545 --> 00:32:13,207
You're the expert,
but at the Muncie College of Business--

405
00:32:13,281 --> 00:32:15,010
Relax, it's only natural...

406
00:32:15,183 --> 00:32:18,710
...in a period of transition for
the more timid element to run for cover.

407
00:32:18,786 --> 00:32:22,483
Like I said, you're the expert
but do you remember the plan I outlined...

408
00:32:22,557 --> 00:32:25,720
...the day I set fire to your....
The day I was promoted?

409
00:32:26,127 --> 00:32:30,291
I do remember and I was impressed.
But that's all forgotten now.

410
00:32:32,467 --> 00:32:33,661
Thank you, Sid.

411
00:32:34,469 --> 00:32:38,064
The reason I mention it is it requires
such a small capital investment....

412
00:32:38,139 --> 00:32:41,404
-There's a huge potential profit...
-Damn it, where's my car?

413
00:32:41,476 --> 00:32:44,502
...given the demographics boom
of the burgeoning middle-class.

414
00:32:44,579 --> 00:32:48,640
So if you agree, I'd like to bounce the idea
off a few people at lunch.

415
00:32:48,716 --> 00:32:49,705
Sure.

416
00:32:49,951 --> 00:32:53,819
Tell whoever you want.
I'd like to hear about it at some point too.

417
00:33:03,164 --> 00:33:04,495
I got gas, Benny.

418
00:33:06,134 --> 00:33:07,465
Tell me about it.

419
00:33:07,935 --> 00:33:10,165
No kidding, Benny. I got gas.

420
00:33:11,005 --> 00:33:12,495
You get the special?

421
00:33:12,840 --> 00:33:13,966
Far from it.

422
00:33:17,979 --> 00:33:19,241
Enter the dame.

423
00:33:20,014 --> 00:33:22,005
There's one in every story.

424
00:33:22,617 --> 00:33:25,211
Ten bucks says she's looking for a handout.

425
00:33:25,553 --> 00:33:28,420
Twenty bucks says not here,
she don't find one.

426
00:33:29,023 --> 00:33:30,684
She's looking for her mark.

427
00:33:30,758 --> 00:33:31,952
She finds him.

428
00:33:32,026 --> 00:33:34,688
She sits down and orders...

429
00:33:36,030 --> 00:33:37,361
...a light lunch.

430
00:33:37,899 --> 00:33:40,094
How will she pay for this lunch?

431
00:33:40,535 --> 00:33:42,332
She looks through her purse.

432
00:33:42,637 --> 00:33:43,661
No money.

433
00:33:44,138 --> 00:33:45,833
The mark notices.

434
00:33:47,275 --> 00:33:48,970
He's not noticing, Benny.

435
00:33:49,043 --> 00:33:50,476
Maybe he's wise.

436
00:33:50,878 --> 00:33:52,368
He don't look wise.

437
00:33:54,549 --> 00:33:55,777
Plan two.

438
00:33:56,117 --> 00:33:57,914
Here come the waterworks.

439
00:33:58,252 --> 00:34:00,311
-Yellowstone.
-Old Faithful.

440
00:34:00,388 --> 00:34:02,253
Hello, Niagara.

441
00:34:02,690 --> 00:34:03,850
He notices.

442
00:34:03,925 --> 00:34:05,324
She's distressed.

443
00:34:05,560 --> 00:34:06,993
He's concerned.

444
00:34:07,562 --> 00:34:09,655
She explains her predicament.

445
00:34:10,031 --> 00:34:11,020
And....

446
00:34:11,699 --> 00:34:13,724
Enter the light lunch.

447
00:34:14,902 --> 00:34:16,995
She's got other problems, of course.

448
00:34:17,071 --> 00:34:18,971
There's illness in the family.

449
00:34:19,407 --> 00:34:22,308
-Her mother needs an operation.
-Urgently.

450
00:34:22,477 --> 00:34:24,138
-Adenoids.
-No, Benny.

451
00:34:25,480 --> 00:34:26,913
Lumbago.

452
00:34:27,682 --> 00:34:30,014
That gag's got whiskers on it.

453
00:34:31,185 --> 00:34:32,777
He ain't biting, Benny.

454
00:34:32,854 --> 00:34:35,687
-She's losing him, Lou.
-Maybe he's wise.

455
00:34:36,324 --> 00:34:38,019
He don't look wise.

456
00:34:38,593 --> 00:34:41,357
-How does she pull this out?
-He's getting away.

457
00:34:41,429 --> 00:34:42,987
She better think fast.

458
00:34:43,331 --> 00:34:44,662
She isn't.

459
00:34:44,999 --> 00:34:46,432
She is!

460
00:34:47,535 --> 00:34:48,900
She's good, Benny.

461
00:34:49,537 --> 00:34:51,027
She's damn good, Lou.

462
00:34:52,406 --> 00:34:54,499
Can I get you boys anything else?

463
00:34:56,811 --> 00:34:57,971
Bromo.

464
00:34:58,780 --> 00:34:59,940
Bromo.

465
00:35:01,916 --> 00:35:05,682
I'm sorry we had to take the stairs.
It was just that horrible elevator boy!

466
00:35:05,753 --> 00:35:08,847
I can't say how much I appreciate
your listening to my story.

467
00:35:08,923 --> 00:35:13,360
I'm lucky to find someone in this bustling
city with a stout heart and a ready ear.

468
00:35:13,928 --> 00:35:16,226
There I was, travelling
through this great country.

469
00:35:16,297 --> 00:35:18,663
Some I met were kind to me,
others exceedingly cruel.

470
00:35:18,733 --> 00:35:21,133
Traveling by motor bus, rail,
even by thumb....

471
00:35:21,202 --> 00:35:22,601
The couch, please.

472
00:35:22,737 --> 00:35:26,138
Hoarding every dollar, counting
every nickel, pinching every penny.

473
00:35:26,407 --> 00:35:29,103
It's been a long road leading
to the coffee shop downstairs.

474
00:35:29,177 --> 00:35:32,544
Not that I'd trade a day, an hour,
a moment of it for anything.

475
00:35:32,880 --> 00:35:34,472
I don't know what came over me.

476
00:35:34,549 --> 00:35:36,847
I guess it was the shock of eating
after so long...

477
00:35:36,918 --> 00:35:39,284
...without the enzymes kicking in
after so long....

478
00:35:43,424 --> 00:35:47,053
Then you couldn't possibly know
what it is to be tired and hungry.

479
00:35:47,261 --> 00:35:48,285
Hungry, anyway.

480
00:35:48,362 --> 00:35:51,490
I don't want to bore you with details
of my life. It's not happy.

481
00:35:51,566 --> 00:35:54,000
Suffice to say I'm jobless,
but not for want of trying.

482
00:35:54,068 --> 00:35:57,697
I'm friendless, with no one to take care
of me and had you not come along...

483
00:35:57,772 --> 00:36:00,468
-...exactly when you did....
-l, myself--

484
00:36:00,608 --> 00:36:02,576
I arrived in town not ten days ago...

485
00:36:02,643 --> 00:36:05,840
...full of dreams, anxious to make my way
in the world...

486
00:36:05,913 --> 00:36:08,711
...a little naive perhaps,
but armed with determination...

487
00:36:08,783 --> 00:36:11,411
...a solid work ethic,
and an indomitable belief in the future...

488
00:36:11,485 --> 00:36:13,385
-l, myself--
-...only to have that belief...

489
00:36:13,454 --> 00:36:16,787
...that unsullied optimism, dashed against
the marble of the workplace.

490
00:36:16,891 --> 00:36:19,917
Such is life. Seek and ye shall find.
Work and ye shall prosper.

491
00:36:19,994 --> 00:36:21,655
-Cigarette?
-No, thank you.

492
00:36:21,762 --> 00:36:24,094
Seek and ye shall find,
work and ye shall prosper.

493
00:36:24,165 --> 00:36:26,929
These were the watchwords,
the ethos of my education...

494
00:36:27,001 --> 00:36:28,491
...the values instilled in me...

495
00:36:28,569 --> 00:36:31,902
...while I was growing up in a town
you've probably never heard of.

496
00:36:31,973 --> 00:36:33,634
-Mind if I join you?
-Be my guest.

497
00:36:33,708 --> 00:36:35,767
A town you've probably never heard of...

498
00:36:35,843 --> 00:36:38,710
...a dusty crossroads of which
you've probably never heard.

499
00:36:40,181 --> 00:36:42,877
Excuse me. Executive washroom.

500
00:36:46,153 --> 00:36:47,313
Are you all right?

501
00:36:49,857 --> 00:36:52,291
Is it your lunch? The chicken a la king?

502
00:36:55,029 --> 00:36:56,656
Is the a la king repeating on you?

503
00:36:57,164 --> 00:36:59,758
No, I'm fine. You were saying?

504
00:37:03,204 --> 00:37:05,604
Values, watchwords, tender years.

505
00:37:06,107 --> 00:37:08,735
A little town you've probably
never heard of:

506
00:37:09,543 --> 00:37:10,874
Muncie, lndiana.

507
00:37:11,846 --> 00:37:13,143
You're from Muncie?

508
00:37:14,315 --> 00:37:15,304
Why, yes.

509
00:37:16,217 --> 00:37:17,479
Do you know it?

510
00:37:34,568 --> 00:37:39,335
"Fight on
Fight on, dear old Muncie

511
00:37:40,107 --> 00:37:44,009
"Fight on
Hoist the gold and blue

512
00:37:44,145 --> 00:37:48,081
"You'll be tattered, torn and hurting

513
00:37:48,149 --> 00:37:52,245
"Once the Munce is done with...

514
00:37:53,020 --> 00:37:54,510
"...you.

515
00:37:59,527 --> 00:38:00,858
"Go...

516
00:38:01,562 --> 00:38:02,494
"Go...

517
00:38:03,431 --> 00:38:04,261
"...Eagles!

518
00:38:04,332 --> 00:38:05,424
"...Eagles!"

519
00:38:09,270 --> 00:38:12,103
A Muncie girl!
What do you know about that?

520
00:38:13,374 --> 00:38:16,605
I'm going to cancel the rest
of my appointments for today...

521
00:38:16,744 --> 00:38:18,644
...and get you a job right here at Hud.

522
00:38:18,713 --> 00:38:20,271
Oh, no! Really--

523
00:38:20,548 --> 00:38:24,040
Don't bother to thank me. It's easy.
I know where a vacancy just came up.

524
00:38:24,185 --> 00:38:25,243
Mailroom.

525
00:38:26,954 --> 00:38:28,683
Good afternoon, this is Norville Barnes.

526
00:38:28,756 --> 00:38:32,214
Barnes! Where the hell have you been?
Where's my voucher?

527
00:38:33,761 --> 00:38:34,785
I'm not sure.

528
00:38:34,929 --> 00:38:37,796
I need that voucher!
I told you a week ago it was important!

529
00:38:39,100 --> 00:38:40,829
I'm president of the company now.

530
00:38:40,901 --> 00:38:44,393
I don't care if you're president
of the company!

531
00:38:44,505 --> 00:38:46,632
I need the voucher now!

532
00:38:47,975 --> 00:38:50,068
Why don't you work in here with me?

533
00:38:50,244 --> 00:38:52,678
Are you familiar with
the mimeograph machine?

534
00:38:52,747 --> 00:38:57,207
Well, of course. I went
to the Muncie Secretarial Polytechnic.

535
00:38:57,485 --> 00:38:59,453
A Muncie girl! Can you beat that?

536
00:39:00,488 --> 00:39:03,150
I just don't know how to thank you,
Mr. Barnes.

537
00:39:03,224 --> 00:39:04,282
Please, Norville.

538
00:39:05,426 --> 00:39:06,950
Go, Eagles!

539
00:39:07,361 --> 00:39:08,726
Go, Eagles!

540
00:39:12,333 --> 00:39:13,823
"Once the Munce...."

541
00:39:14,135 --> 00:39:15,568
Holy moly!

542
00:39:15,703 --> 00:39:18,900
Is this guy from Chumpsville?
I even pulled the old mother routine.

543
00:39:18,973 --> 00:39:19,667
Adenoids?

544
00:39:19,740 --> 00:39:20,672
Lumbago.

545
00:39:21,275 --> 00:39:22,867
That gag's got whiskers on it.

546
00:39:22,943 --> 00:39:25,377
I'm telling you, the Hudsucker Board's
up to something.

547
00:39:25,446 --> 00:39:28,415
What's a six-letter word
for an affliction of the hypothalamus?

548
00:39:28,482 --> 00:39:31,610
It's a cinch. Goiter.
It's a cinch this guy isn't in on it.

549
00:39:31,685 --> 00:39:32,709
She's right here.

550
00:39:32,787 --> 00:39:35,017
How much time to make the late final?

551
00:39:35,856 --> 00:39:38,290
Hi, Chief, just the person
I wanted to apologize to.

552
00:39:38,359 --> 00:39:39,621
About seven minutes.

553
00:39:39,794 --> 00:39:41,955
I was all wet about your ldea Man.

554
00:39:42,563 --> 00:39:47,057
Well, thanks for being so generous.
It is human and you are divine.

555
00:39:47,568 --> 00:39:49,399
No, he's no faker.

556
00:39:49,937 --> 00:39:53,304
He's a 100% real McCoy,
beware of imitations, genuine article.

557
00:39:53,641 --> 00:39:56,974
The guy's a real moron,
as in a five-letter word for imbecile.

558
00:39:57,144 --> 00:40:00,045
As pure a specimen as I've ever run across.

559
00:40:01,315 --> 00:40:02,748
If I'm not an expert...

560
00:40:02,817 --> 00:40:06,344
...then my name isn't Amy Archer
and I never won the Pulitzer.

561
00:40:06,787 --> 00:40:07,811
In 1957.

562
00:40:09,757 --> 00:40:11,782
My series on the reunited triplets.

563
00:40:12,126 --> 00:40:14,993
Come down here, hammerhead,
and I'll show it to you!

564
00:40:15,062 --> 00:40:18,054
What's a three-letter word
for a flightless bird?

565
00:40:18,165 --> 00:40:19,462
Not now, I'm busy.

566
00:40:19,733 --> 00:40:23,669
I said, "hammerhead" as in a ten-letter
word for a smug, bullying newspaper man.

567
00:40:23,838 --> 00:40:25,635
Gnu. That's G-N-U.

568
00:40:25,706 --> 00:40:29,267
Couldn't find the Empire State Building
with a compass, map and a guide.

569
00:40:29,343 --> 00:40:30,105
Or emu?

570
00:40:30,177 --> 00:40:33,908
That's just potatoes. Here's the gravy.
The chump really liked me.

571
00:40:34,081 --> 00:40:36,914
-A Muncie girl!
-Better off falling for a rattlesnake.

572
00:40:37,084 --> 00:40:39,678
This guy's just a patsy
and I'm gonna find out what for.

573
00:40:39,753 --> 00:40:44,190
There's a real story here, some kind
of plot, set-up.... Did I tell you?

574
00:40:44,291 --> 00:40:46,191
-He didn't offer you money?
-A sawbuck!

575
00:40:46,260 --> 00:40:48,285
Ten smackers! Let's grab a highball!

576
00:40:48,362 --> 00:40:49,795
On Norville Barnes.

577
00:40:51,165 --> 00:40:51,824
Copy!

578
00:41:21,729 --> 00:41:23,754
Miss Smith, would you come in
and take a letter?

579
00:41:25,065 --> 00:41:26,760
Of all the cockamamie....

580
00:41:29,103 --> 00:41:31,901
Did you see the front page
of today's Manhattan Argus?

581
00:41:31,972 --> 00:41:36,136
I didn't bother to read the article.
I didn't think the picture did you justice.

582
00:41:36,810 --> 00:41:38,300
The picture's fine.

583
00:41:38,379 --> 00:41:40,904
It's what that knuckle-headed dame
wrote underneath.

584
00:41:42,249 --> 00:41:43,511
Take this down.

585
00:41:43,751 --> 00:41:45,184
Dear Miss Archer:

586
00:41:46,053 --> 00:41:49,580
I call you "Miss" because you seem to have
missed the boat completely.

587
00:41:49,657 --> 00:41:51,648
How would you know if I'm an imbecile...

588
00:41:51,725 --> 00:41:54,694
...when you didn't have the guts
to interview me man-to-man!

589
00:41:54,762 --> 00:41:56,354
Change "man-to-man" to "face-to-face."

590
00:41:56,430 --> 00:41:59,866
No, change "face-to-face" to "eye-to-eye"
and "guts" to "common decency."

591
00:41:59,934 --> 00:42:02,095
These wild speculations
about my intelligence...

592
00:42:02,169 --> 00:42:04,501
...these preposterous inventions
would be better suited...

593
00:42:04,572 --> 00:42:07,439
...for the pages of Amazing Tales Magazine.

594
00:42:07,675 --> 00:42:10,200
If the editors of the Manhattan Argus
see fit...

595
00:42:10,277 --> 00:42:14,646
...to publish the work of a disordered mind,
perhaps they will see fit to publish this.

596
00:42:14,715 --> 00:42:15,875
But I doubt it.

597
00:42:15,950 --> 00:42:19,943
I most seriously doubt it. I doubt also
you could find a home at Amazing Tales...

598
00:42:20,020 --> 00:42:23,512
...a periodical which I have enjoyed
for many years. Sincerely...

599
00:42:23,857 --> 00:42:25,051
...et cetera.

600
00:42:32,399 --> 00:42:34,094
Is that all, Mr. Barnes?

601
00:42:36,470 --> 00:42:39,962
You know me, Amy, better than this dame.
Do you think I'm an imbecile?

602
00:42:40,307 --> 00:42:41,672
Well, I'm sure l....

603
00:42:42,009 --> 00:42:45,376
Tell the truth. I trust you.
I place a lot of stock in your opinion.

604
00:42:47,314 --> 00:42:49,111
Oh, sure, you're biased.

605
00:42:49,550 --> 00:42:51,040
You're a fellow Muncian.

606
00:42:52,019 --> 00:42:53,680
But let me ask you a question:

607
00:42:53,988 --> 00:42:56,286
Would an imbecile come up with this?

608
00:43:02,663 --> 00:43:04,153
I designed it myself.

609
00:43:05,332 --> 00:43:08,529
This sweet baby will put Hudsucker
right back on top.

610
00:43:11,272 --> 00:43:12,534
You know, for kids.

611
00:43:15,943 --> 00:43:18,173
Why don't I just type this up?

612
00:43:18,345 --> 00:43:21,246
That won't be necessary.
I shouldn't send it.

613
00:43:21,415 --> 00:43:23,406
She's just doing her job, I guess.

614
00:43:24,018 --> 00:43:26,111
I don't know, maybe she does deserve it.

615
00:43:26,720 --> 00:43:29,746
Maybe she should have come in here
and faced you man-to-man.

616
00:43:29,823 --> 00:43:33,691
-She probably had a deadline.
-She still could've gotten your side...

617
00:43:34,061 --> 00:43:35,323
...for the record.

618
00:43:35,396 --> 00:43:38,092
It's done now. What's the use
of grousing about it?

619
00:43:38,365 --> 00:43:41,266
Forget the letter,
I just had to blow off steam.

620
00:43:41,735 --> 00:43:43,828
She's probably just a little confused.

621
00:43:45,272 --> 00:43:46,136
"Confused?"

622
00:43:46,206 --> 00:43:49,573
Probably a fast-talking career gal,
thinks she's one of the boys.

623
00:43:49,643 --> 00:43:51,543
Probably is, if you know what I mean.

624
00:43:51,612 --> 00:43:54,206
I'm quite sure I don't know what you mean.

625
00:43:54,315 --> 00:43:57,182
Probably suffers from one
of these complexes they have nowadays.

626
00:43:57,251 --> 00:44:01,051
It's obvious. She's probably
very unattractive and bitter about it.

627
00:44:01,221 --> 00:44:02,381
Is that it?

628
00:44:03,257 --> 00:44:07,091
She probably dresses in men's clothing,
drinks with the guys at the local bar...

629
00:44:07,161 --> 00:44:11,222
...hobnobs with some smooth-talking heel
reporter named Biff or Smoocher or--

630
00:44:11,298 --> 00:44:12,060
Smitty.

631
00:44:12,132 --> 00:44:14,657
Exactly. I bet she's ugly, real ugly.

632
00:44:14,735 --> 00:44:17,169
Otherwise, why isn't her picture
next to her byline?

633
00:44:17,237 --> 00:44:20,798
Maybe she puts her work
ahead of her personal appearance.

634
00:44:20,974 --> 00:44:22,874
I bet that's what she tells herself.

635
00:44:22,943 --> 00:44:26,174
But you and I know
she's a dried-up, bitter old maid.

636
00:44:27,014 --> 00:44:29,539
How about we grab a little dinner
and a show after work?

637
00:44:29,616 --> 00:44:31,516
I was thinking maybe The King and I?

638
00:44:32,653 --> 00:44:33,984
How about Oklahoma?

639
00:44:34,221 --> 00:44:36,746
You don't know a thing about that woman!

640
00:44:36,824 --> 00:44:40,760
You don't know who she really is!
Only a numbskull thinks he knows things...

641
00:44:40,828 --> 00:44:43,058
...about things he knows nothing about.

642
00:44:44,932 --> 00:44:46,661
Say, what gives?

643
00:46:53,894 --> 00:46:57,455
The inventory of the Jacksonville facility
should be reduced...

644
00:46:57,631 --> 00:47:00,725
...by 15%. Memo from the desk
of Sidney J. Mussburger--

645
00:47:00,901 --> 00:47:03,233
What are you doing, Miss Archer?

646
00:47:12,746 --> 00:47:15,613
Who are you?
How did you know who I am?

647
00:47:18,185 --> 00:47:21,552
I suspect Old Moses knows
just about everything...

648
00:47:22,089 --> 00:47:24,523
...Ieastways if it concerns Hudsucker.

649
00:47:25,025 --> 00:47:27,084
Who are you? What do you do here?

650
00:47:27,427 --> 00:47:29,327
I keep the old circle turning.

651
00:47:29,763 --> 00:47:31,958
This old clock needs plenty of care.

652
00:47:32,766 --> 00:47:34,529
Time is money, Miss Archer.

653
00:47:35,202 --> 00:47:38,000
Money drives that old global economy...

654
00:47:38,071 --> 00:47:40,471
...and keeps Big Daddy Earth
spinning around.

655
00:47:40,607 --> 00:47:43,269
See, without that capital formation--

656
00:47:45,178 --> 00:47:47,442
You won't tell anyone about me, will you?

657
00:47:47,614 --> 00:47:50,048
I don't tell no one nothing...

658
00:47:50,784 --> 00:47:52,217
...unless they ask.

659
00:47:52,619 --> 00:47:54,610
That just ain't Old Moses' way.

660
00:47:55,489 --> 00:47:57,150
If you know everything about Hudsucker...

661
00:47:57,224 --> 00:48:00,785
...tell me why the board decided
to make Norville Barnes president?

662
00:48:01,161 --> 00:48:03,823
That even surprised Old Moses at first.

663
00:48:04,431 --> 00:48:06,592
I didn't think the board was that smart.

664
00:48:06,667 --> 00:48:07,599
"That smart?"

665
00:48:07,668 --> 00:48:10,637
But then I figured it out.
They did it because...

666
00:48:10,704 --> 00:48:14,538
...they figured young Norville for
an imbecile, like some other people I know.

667
00:48:15,042 --> 00:48:18,205
Why on earth would the board
want a nitwit to be president?

668
00:48:18,445 --> 00:48:22,506
Because they're little piglets.
They're trying to inspire panic...

669
00:48:23,150 --> 00:48:26,586
...make that stock cheap so they can
snatch it all up for themselves.

670
00:48:26,820 --> 00:48:30,278
But Norville's got some tricks
up his sleeve. He does.

671
00:48:30,924 --> 00:48:32,414
"You know, for kids?"

672
00:48:34,294 --> 00:48:37,058
Yeah, he's a smart one, that Norville.

673
00:48:37,898 --> 00:48:42,801
But I guess you don't really know him
any better than that board does, do you?

674
00:48:43,503 --> 00:48:44,435
Maybe l--

675
00:48:44,504 --> 00:48:49,066
And only some kind of knuckle-head thinks
she knows things about things....

676
00:48:50,344 --> 00:48:51,902
When she don't....

677
00:48:53,180 --> 00:48:54,408
How'd that go?

678
00:48:54,648 --> 00:48:56,445
Well, it's hardly the same.

679
00:48:56,750 --> 00:48:58,980
You don't even know your own self.

680
00:48:59,353 --> 00:49:02,914
You ain't exactly the genuine article,
are you, Miss Archer?

681
00:49:03,256 --> 00:49:08,250
In connection with my job, sometimes
I have to go undercover, as it were.

682
00:49:08,362 --> 00:49:09,852
I don't mean that.

683
00:49:10,197 --> 00:49:14,031
Why are you pretending to be
such a hard old sourpuss?

684
00:49:14,668 --> 00:49:16,795
Ain't going to never make you happy!

685
00:49:18,772 --> 00:49:20,399
I'm happy enough.

686
00:49:26,380 --> 00:49:28,245
I got gears to see to.

687
00:49:33,120 --> 00:49:34,644
I'm plenty happy!

688
00:49:45,365 --> 00:49:46,593
I can't print that!

689
00:49:46,667 --> 00:49:50,467
Why not? It's true. The board's using him
to depress the stock and buy it cheap.

690
00:49:50,537 --> 00:49:53,472
It's pure speculation!
They'd have my butt in a satchel!

691
00:49:54,474 --> 00:49:55,964
They'll buy that stock--

692
00:49:56,043 --> 00:49:59,638
You don't know anything. They haven't
bought it. What are they waiting for?

693
00:49:59,713 --> 00:50:00,407
I don't know.

694
00:50:00,480 --> 00:50:02,846
Amy's hunches are usually pretty good.

695
00:50:02,916 --> 00:50:05,680
You don't accuse somebody
of stock manipulation on a hunch!

696
00:50:05,752 --> 00:50:08,653
Our readers aren't interested
in sensationalism, gossip...

697
00:50:08,722 --> 00:50:10,087
...unsupported speculation!

698
00:50:10,157 --> 00:50:13,149
Facts! Figures! Those are the tools
of the newspaper trade.

699
00:50:13,260 --> 00:50:16,957
It's as if you're trying to take the heat
off him. Like you've gone soft on him.

700
00:50:17,030 --> 00:50:19,191
Come on, Chief. That's a low blow.

701
00:50:19,266 --> 00:50:22,030
Archer's not going to go gooey
for a corn-fed idiot.

702
00:50:22,102 --> 00:50:25,538
I was out of line. But you're out of line
with this stock-swindle story.

703
00:50:25,605 --> 00:50:28,199
Give me more of that
"moron from Sheboygan" stuff.

704
00:50:28,275 --> 00:50:29,435
-Muncie.
-Whatever.

705
00:50:29,509 --> 00:50:31,170
That's what sells newspapers!

706
00:50:31,244 --> 00:50:33,940
I've got a harder story:
"The Sap From The City Desk! "

707
00:50:34,014 --> 00:50:36,539
-Watch it!
-It's about a dim-witted editor who--

708
00:50:36,616 --> 00:50:37,947
Easy, tough guy.

709
00:50:41,288 --> 00:50:43,415
Does this suit look mannish to you?

710
00:50:43,523 --> 00:50:45,650
Yeah, sure. Let's grab a highball.

711
00:50:46,626 --> 00:50:47,684
Back off!

712
00:50:48,128 --> 00:50:49,288
Smoocher!

713
00:50:52,099 --> 00:50:53,327
What gives?

714
00:51:09,182 --> 00:51:12,174
A man of great managerial potency.

715
00:51:12,786 --> 00:51:15,118
My husband is also a president.

716
00:51:15,288 --> 00:51:18,621
Sears Braithwaite of Bullard.
Do you know him?

717
00:51:18,892 --> 00:51:21,019
Your companion is an ode!

718
00:51:21,194 --> 00:51:23,822
A lyric! Are you betrothed?

719
00:51:23,930 --> 00:51:26,455
Amy works in my office. She runs--

720
00:51:26,533 --> 00:51:28,694
Oh, the folly of youth!

721
00:51:28,869 --> 00:51:30,860
Those green remembered hills!

722
00:51:30,937 --> 00:51:34,202
That bourn from which no traveler returns.

723
00:51:34,708 --> 00:51:37,040
I once ran the mimeograph for Sidney.

724
00:51:37,210 --> 00:51:40,304
Though engaged at the time
to quelqu'un d'autre...

725
00:51:40,714 --> 00:51:44,047
...my water-cooler romance
became a mad passion.

726
00:51:44,484 --> 00:51:47,385
Un amour fou. Une folie a deux.

727
00:51:49,656 --> 00:51:52,352
I'm brushing up on my French
with the most charming man...

728
00:51:52,425 --> 00:51:56,088
-...Pierre of 5th Avenue. Do you know him?
-Do you know him?

729
00:51:56,163 --> 00:52:00,827
Sidney and I are planning a trip
to Paris and points continental.

730
00:52:04,171 --> 00:52:05,331
Aren't we, dear?

731
00:52:06,239 --> 00:52:10,005
Sure. I'd like to borrow Norville
for a while, if you don't mind.

732
00:52:11,578 --> 00:52:13,239
Well, frankly, l....

733
00:52:13,580 --> 00:52:16,344
You have a very charming wife, Mr.... Sid.

734
00:52:16,516 --> 00:52:17,813
So they tell me.

735
00:52:18,485 --> 00:52:21,682
Let me shepherd you
through some of the introductions here.

736
00:52:21,855 --> 00:52:23,846
Try not to talk too much.

737
00:52:24,357 --> 00:52:26,518
Some of our biggest stockholders are....

738
00:52:27,260 --> 00:52:28,887
Scratch that. Say whatever you like.

739
00:52:28,962 --> 00:52:31,760
Shake hands with
Sears Braithwaite of Bullard.

740
00:52:32,098 --> 00:52:33,725
Glad to know you, Barnes.

741
00:52:34,100 --> 00:52:35,897
This is Zebulon Cardozo...

742
00:52:35,969 --> 00:52:39,097
...one of Hudsucker's largest
and most loyal stockholders.

743
00:52:39,206 --> 00:52:41,606
What's this I hear
about you being an imbecile?

744
00:52:41,675 --> 00:52:43,336
What's ailing you, boy?

745
00:52:43,476 --> 00:52:47,606
Last week, my stock was worth twice
what it is now. I think I'll sell...

746
00:52:47,681 --> 00:52:51,742
...the whole kit and caboodle, boy,
unless I see a vast improvement.

747
00:52:52,118 --> 00:52:54,712
What you've got here, son, is a range war!

748
00:52:54,888 --> 00:52:58,756
You gonna have to circle our wagons
or I'm gonna get out of your wagon train.

749
00:53:00,327 --> 00:53:02,522
No need for concern, sir.
It's only natural...

750
00:53:02,629 --> 00:53:05,826
...in a period of transition for the more
timid elements to run for cover.

751
00:53:05,899 --> 00:53:08,925
Yellow? I'll show you yellow, boy!

752
00:53:09,669 --> 00:53:12,695
You mind now and quit acting
like such an old grizzly.

753
00:53:12,906 --> 00:53:14,771
Step lively here, Norville.

754
00:53:15,308 --> 00:53:18,505
I'm sorry, I thought maybe if I showed him
the long view--

755
00:53:18,778 --> 00:53:21,576
And this is Thorstensen Finlandson...

756
00:53:21,815 --> 00:53:24,579
...who heads a radical, splinter group
of disgruntled investors.

757
00:53:24,651 --> 00:53:26,084
Pleased to meet you.

758
00:53:26,152 --> 00:53:29,679
It might interest you to know I studied
a little Finnish in high school.

759
00:53:29,756 --> 00:53:31,417
I hope I'm not too rusty.

760
00:53:39,165 --> 00:53:42,692
Ladies and gentlemen, distinguished
members of the Hudsucker Board...

761
00:53:42,769 --> 00:53:47,001
...I give you the Rajah of Romance,
the Ministereo of Moonlight...

762
00:53:47,374 --> 00:53:49,740
...the incredible, the unforgettable...

763
00:53:49,843 --> 00:53:52,778
...Mr. Vic Tenetta!

764
00:53:59,519 --> 00:54:01,248
"Rajah." I like that.

765
00:54:44,331 --> 00:54:45,730
What happened?

766
00:54:47,167 --> 00:54:51,661
Nothing. Just the more timid investors
are no longer running for cover.

767
00:54:51,838 --> 00:54:52,964
Let me look.

768
00:54:53,573 --> 00:54:54,938
Sid found me the ice pack.

769
00:54:55,008 --> 00:54:57,704
Let me hold it or you'll have a real shiner.

770
00:54:59,112 --> 00:55:01,876
I guess people are pretty hot
over this imbecile story.

771
00:55:02,515 --> 00:55:03,846
I'm sorry.

772
00:55:04,551 --> 00:55:08,510
It's not your fault. You've the one person
standing by me through all this.

773
00:55:08,588 --> 00:55:11,386
Norville, there's something
I have to tell you.

774
00:55:12,359 --> 00:55:13,417
You see...

775
00:55:14,094 --> 00:55:16,062
...I'm not really a secretary.

776
00:55:17,030 --> 00:55:18,190
I know that, Amy.

777
00:55:18,264 --> 00:55:19,253
You do?

778
00:55:19,466 --> 00:55:22,594
I understand you're not very skilled yet
in the secretarial arts...

779
00:55:22,669 --> 00:55:25,797
...but I'll tell you a secret:
I'm not that skilled as president.

780
00:55:25,872 --> 00:55:29,308
-I know I put up a big front, but--
-I believe in you, Norville.

781
00:55:30,977 --> 00:55:32,069
At least...

782
00:55:32,612 --> 00:55:35,046
...I believe in your intentions.

783
00:55:35,281 --> 00:55:38,739
I don't blame them, really.
I suppose I have made a mess of things.

784
00:55:39,386 --> 00:55:41,650
Those folks have to protect
their investment.

785
00:55:41,721 --> 00:55:43,313
Most of them are very nice people.

786
00:55:43,390 --> 00:55:46,826
Listen, you can't trust people here
like you did in Muncie.

787
00:55:46,893 --> 00:55:48,952
Certain people are--

788
00:55:49,029 --> 00:55:52,988
Did you ever go to the top of Larson's
feed tower and look out over the town?

789
00:55:53,967 --> 00:55:55,332
On Farm Route 17?

790
00:55:55,735 --> 00:55:58,169
Oh, yes, in Muncie.

791
00:55:59,406 --> 00:56:02,068
No, Vidalia. Farm Route 17.

792
00:56:03,777 --> 00:56:07,178
Seventeen. Yes, l....
Well, no, no. I never really--

793
00:56:08,982 --> 00:56:12,748
The guys from the Varsity Squad
would bring their dates up there...

794
00:56:13,820 --> 00:56:15,151
...to hold hands.

795
00:56:15,989 --> 00:56:18,219
Of course, I never made Varsity.

796
00:56:20,927 --> 00:56:22,724
There's a place I go now.

797
00:56:23,596 --> 00:56:26,622
Cutest little place near my apartment
in Greenwich Village.

798
00:56:26,699 --> 00:56:28,667
It's called "Ann's 440."

799
00:56:29,002 --> 00:56:30,435
It's a beatnik bar.

800
00:56:30,503 --> 00:56:31,936
-You don't say?
-Yes.

801
00:56:32,005 --> 00:56:32,994
A beatnik bar.

802
00:56:33,073 --> 00:56:36,600
You can get carrot juice or ltalian coffee
and the people there...

803
00:56:37,210 --> 00:56:38,939
Well, none of them quite fit in.

804
00:56:39,546 --> 00:56:40,774
You'd love it.

805
00:56:41,281 --> 00:56:42,714
Come there with me.

806
00:56:43,216 --> 00:56:46,083
There's a marathon poetry-reading
on New Year's Eve. I go every year.

807
00:56:46,152 --> 00:56:48,416
-It's marvelous!
-Every year?

808
00:56:50,623 --> 00:56:55,026
Well, this year, if it's good,
I plan to make it a tradition.

809
00:56:57,297 --> 00:56:59,231
My, it certainly is beautiful.

810
00:57:00,033 --> 00:57:01,557
The people...

811
00:57:02,035 --> 00:57:03,559
...Iook like ants.

812
00:57:04,737 --> 00:57:07,900
The Hindus, and the beatniks also,
say that...

813
00:57:08,475 --> 00:57:11,239
...in our next lives some of us
will come back as ants.

814
00:57:11,711 --> 00:57:15,875
Some will be butterflies, others will be
elephants or creatures of the sea.

815
00:57:16,049 --> 00:57:17,539
What a beautiful thought.

816
00:57:17,684 --> 00:57:20,380
What do you think you were
in a previous life?

817
00:57:21,488 --> 00:57:23,080
Oh, I don't know.

818
00:57:23,890 --> 00:57:25,380
Maybe I was just...

819
00:57:25,825 --> 00:57:29,955
...a fast-talking career gal
who thought she was one of the boys.

820
00:57:30,063 --> 00:57:31,223
Oh, no, Amy.

821
00:57:31,498 --> 00:57:34,365
Pardon me for saying so,
but I find that very far-fetched.

822
00:57:34,501 --> 00:57:38,494
-There really is something I must tell you.
-That person would come back as a hog.

823
00:57:38,571 --> 00:57:41,301
I find it more likely that you were...

824
00:57:42,642 --> 00:57:43,700
...a gazelle...

825
00:57:44,677 --> 00:57:48,306
...with long, graceful legs,
gamboling through the underbrush.

826
00:57:49,182 --> 00:57:50,774
Perhaps we met once.

827
00:57:51,518 --> 00:57:54,214
A chance encounter in a forest glade.

828
00:57:56,189 --> 00:57:58,714
I must have been an antelope or an ibex.

829
00:57:59,926 --> 00:58:03,487
The times we must've had
foraging together for sustenance...

830
00:58:04,430 --> 00:58:07,024
...snorfling water
from a mountain stream...

831
00:58:07,600 --> 00:58:11,195
...picking the grubs and burrs
from one another's coats.

832
00:58:13,940 --> 00:58:18,502
Or perhaps we simply touched horns
briefly and went our separate ways.

833
00:58:19,812 --> 00:58:22,440
Oh, I wish it were that simple, Norville.

834
00:58:23,883 --> 00:58:28,081
I wish I was still a gazelle
and you were an antelope...

835
00:58:28,955 --> 00:58:30,286
...or an ibex.

836
00:58:34,894 --> 00:58:36,521
Can I at least call you...

837
00:58:36,829 --> 00:58:37,887
...deer?

838
00:58:41,034 --> 00:58:42,160
You're funny.

839
00:58:42,235 --> 00:58:45,500
Seriously, Amy, it's what
your beatnik friends call "karma."

840
00:58:45,738 --> 00:58:46,568
Karma.

841
00:58:46,639 --> 00:58:49,608
The great circle of life, death and rebirth.

842
00:58:49,776 --> 00:58:53,473
I think I heard of that.
What goes around comes around.

843
00:58:53,580 --> 00:58:57,107
That's it. A great wheel
that gives us all what we deserve.

844
00:58:58,484 --> 00:59:01,715
I've go to show Sid and all the guys
I deserve their confidence.

845
00:59:01,788 --> 00:59:04,279
Tomorrow's my big presentation
to the board.

846
00:59:06,759 --> 00:59:07,987
Kiss me, Amy!

847
00:59:08,361 --> 00:59:09,919
Kiss me once for luck.

848
00:59:11,331 --> 00:59:12,593
Sure, Norville.

849
00:59:54,040 --> 00:59:55,405
You know, for kids!

850
00:59:55,708 --> 00:59:59,576
It has economy, simplicity, low
production cost, potential for mass appeal.

851
00:59:59,646 --> 01:00:01,944
All that spells out great profitability.

852
01:00:02,015 --> 01:00:04,745
I had the boys at R&D
make this prototype...

853
01:00:04,817 --> 01:00:06,785
...so our discussion
could have some focus...

854
01:00:06,853 --> 01:00:10,755
...and to give you gentleman a firsthand
look at how exciting this gizmo is.

855
01:00:10,823 --> 01:00:14,224
It's fun, healthy, good exercise,
and the kids'll love it.

856
01:00:14,360 --> 01:00:17,420
We put a little sand inside
to make the experience more pleasant.

857
01:00:17,497 --> 01:00:20,830
The great part is we don't have
to charge an arm and a leg.

858
01:00:23,469 --> 01:00:26,336
-What if you tire before it's done?
-Does it have rules?

859
01:00:26,406 --> 01:00:28,567
-Can more than one play?
-Why is it a game?

860
01:00:28,641 --> 01:00:30,233
-ls it a game?
-Will it break?

861
01:00:30,310 --> 01:00:32,505
-lt better break eventually.
-ls there an object?

862
01:00:32,578 --> 01:00:35,240
-What if you tire before it's done?
-Does it have batteries?

863
01:00:35,315 --> 01:00:38,182
-Could we charge extra for them?
-ls it safe for toddlers?

864
01:00:38,251 --> 01:00:40,651
-How do you know you're finished?
-How does it stop?

865
01:00:40,720 --> 01:00:43,348
-ls that a boy's model?
-Can a parent assemble it?

866
01:00:43,456 --> 01:00:47,688
-What if you tire before it's done?
-ls there a larger model for the obese?

867
01:00:47,760 --> 01:00:49,955
What the hell is it?

868
01:00:50,029 --> 01:00:51,360
Well, it's....

869
01:00:55,168 --> 01:00:56,260
Brilliant!

870
01:00:58,171 --> 01:00:59,263
Genius.

871
01:01:00,340 --> 01:01:03,867
It's exactly what Hudsucker lndustry needs
at this juncture.

872
01:01:04,777 --> 01:01:09,237
Even a blind man can tell you
there'll be an enormous demand for this...

873
01:01:10,717 --> 01:01:11,775
...this....

874
01:01:12,685 --> 01:01:13,743
Congratulations.

875
01:01:13,820 --> 01:01:16,345
You've outdone yourself.
You've reinvented the wheel.

876
01:01:16,422 --> 01:01:19,391
I'll recommend to the board
that we proceed immediately...

877
01:01:21,094 --> 01:01:22,459
...and that the...

878
01:01:24,197 --> 01:01:26,927
...dingus be mass-produced
with all deliberate speed.

879
01:01:27,333 --> 01:01:29,096
Although, you realize...

880
01:01:29,569 --> 01:01:30,831
...of course...

881
01:01:34,040 --> 01:01:35,405
...as president...

882
01:01:35,742 --> 01:01:37,733
...the ultimate decision is yours.

883
01:01:38,945 --> 01:01:40,207
I'm for it.

884
01:02:28,961 --> 01:02:30,258
The Flying Doughnut!

885
01:02:30,329 --> 01:02:32,695
-The Dancing Dingus!
-The Belly-Go-Round.

886
01:02:32,765 --> 01:02:34,027
The Swingerina!

887
01:02:34,100 --> 01:02:35,590
The Wacky Circumference!

888
01:02:35,635 --> 01:02:37,466
Uncle Midriff!

889
01:03:08,267 --> 01:03:10,064
-We need something short!
-Sharp!

890
01:03:10,136 --> 01:03:10,864
Snappy!

891
01:03:10,937 --> 01:03:13,428
-With a little jazz!
-The Shazzammeter!

892
01:03:13,473 --> 01:03:15,703
-The Hipster!
-The Daddy-O!

893
01:03:56,983 --> 01:03:58,678
-The Hoopsucker.
-The Hudswinger.

894
01:03:58,751 --> 01:04:00,981
-The Hoopsucker!
-The Hudswinger!

895
01:04:01,053 --> 01:04:02,782
-The Hoopsucker!
-The Hudswinger!

896
01:04:30,883 --> 01:04:33,044
-Fellas!
-You got something?

897
01:04:34,754 --> 01:04:36,517
I got something!

898
01:07:48,647 --> 01:07:52,811
Rockwell News presents: Tidbits of Time.

899
01:07:53,185 --> 01:07:55,881
World news in pictures, we kid you not!

900
01:07:56,288 --> 01:07:59,519
As Old Man 1958 hobbles
towards his finish...

901
01:08:00,092 --> 01:08:02,526
...Barnes is the name
on every American lip.

902
01:08:02,695 --> 01:08:06,222
Norville Barnes, young president
of Hudsucker Industries...

903
01:08:06,298 --> 01:08:09,961
...a boy bred in the heartland,
but now the toast of New York.

904
01:08:10,436 --> 01:08:14,964
Barnes is the brainy inventor of America's
craziest craze: The Hula Hoop!

905
01:08:15,508 --> 01:08:19,205
Reaping huge profits for his company
and winning the hearts...

906
01:08:19,512 --> 01:08:22,037
...and hips of every youngster in America!

907
01:08:23,516 --> 01:08:25,006
Did I say youngster?

908
01:08:25,217 --> 01:08:28,209
Here's Mom taking a break
from her household chores...

909
01:08:28,954 --> 01:08:31,445
...and even Dad is swinging into the act!

910
01:08:33,058 --> 01:08:37,859
Cards, letters, congratulations come
pouring in from Kankakee to Petaluma...

911
01:08:38,230 --> 01:08:41,427
...including one very special
long-distance call.

912
01:08:41,700 --> 01:08:43,634
He's on! He's on the line!

913
01:08:50,342 --> 01:08:52,606
Hello, Norville. This is the President.

914
01:08:53,078 --> 01:08:56,570
I just wanted to congratulate you.
I'm very proud of you.

915
01:08:57,216 --> 01:08:59,582
Mrs. Eisenhower is very proud of you.

916
01:08:59,952 --> 01:09:02,512
The American people
are very proud of you.

917
01:09:09,595 --> 01:09:12,587
How'd you come up with the idea
for the Hula Hoop?

918
01:09:12,965 --> 01:09:14,899
It was no great idea, really.

919
01:09:15,000 --> 01:09:18,766
A thing like this takes a whole company
to put together. I'm grateful.

920
01:09:19,071 --> 01:09:21,972
Did you have any idea
there'd be such a huge response?

921
01:09:22,041 --> 01:09:25,135
Frankly, I don't think anybody
expected this much hoopla.

922
01:09:27,046 --> 01:09:30,482
"Hoopla on the Hula Hoop."
Can we quote you on that, Mr. Barnes?

923
01:09:30,616 --> 01:09:32,049
Sure, I guess.

924
01:09:32,751 --> 01:09:35,117
Will you give yourself a nice, fat raise?

925
01:09:36,388 --> 01:09:37,582
Come on, you guys.

926
01:09:45,197 --> 01:09:49,964
What scientific principle explains
the motion of this wheel of wonder?

927
01:09:50,035 --> 01:09:52,196
The dingus is quite simple, really.

928
01:09:52,471 --> 01:09:56,635
It operates on the same principles that
keep the earth spinning around the sun...

929
01:09:56,709 --> 01:10:01,203
...and that keeps you from flying off
the earth into the cold reaches of space...

930
01:10:01,313 --> 01:10:03,838
...where you would die
like a miserable Schwein.

931
01:10:03,916 --> 01:10:06,009
Yes, the principle is the same...

932
01:10:06,485 --> 01:10:10,683
...except for the piece of grit
they put in to make the experience...

933
01:10:11,457 --> 01:10:12,617
...more pleasant.

934
01:10:12,691 --> 01:10:15,421
Yes, it's hula-hula everywhere!

935
01:10:15,494 --> 01:10:18,258
From the parties of the Park Avenue
smart set...

936
01:10:21,433 --> 01:10:25,096
...to sweethearts who want
to be married in the swing of things.

937
01:10:29,475 --> 01:10:32,842
Did the board consider you an "ldea Man"
when they promoted you?

938
01:10:32,912 --> 01:10:36,473
I guess. I don't think they promoted me
because they thought I was a schmo.

939
01:10:36,548 --> 01:10:39,847
What's the next big idea for you
and Hudsucker lndustries?

940
01:10:39,919 --> 01:10:43,320
I don't know. An idea like this sweet baby
doesn't just come overnight.

941
01:10:43,389 --> 01:10:47,655
Although, I'll tell you one thing:
I certainly didn't expect all this hoopla.

942
01:10:48,460 --> 01:10:50,018
You can quote me on that.

943
01:10:57,670 --> 01:11:00,867
Rumpus Magazine has called you
the most eligible bachelor of the year.

944
01:11:00,940 --> 01:11:04,068
And society pages have been linking you
with fashion model Za-Za.

945
01:11:04,143 --> 01:11:08,170
There's no truth to the rumors.
We're just dear friends. Isn't that right?

946
01:11:15,354 --> 01:11:19,620
How do you respond to the charges that
you're out of ideas? Have you run dry?

947
01:11:19,758 --> 01:11:23,717
Not at all. Just this week I came up
with several new sweet ideas.

948
01:11:24,096 --> 01:11:28,533
A larger model Hula Hoop for the portly,
a battery option for the lazy or spastic.

949
01:11:28,667 --> 01:11:31,033
A model with extra sand
for the hard-of-hearing.

950
01:11:31,103 --> 01:11:32,764
I'm earning my keep.

951
01:11:32,838 --> 01:11:35,500
Speaking of that,
do you expect to get a raise?

952
01:11:35,808 --> 01:11:39,869
By anyone's account I single-handedly
have saved Hudsucker lndustries.

953
01:11:39,979 --> 01:11:44,575
Our stock is worth more now than ever.
Yes, I expect to be compensated for that.

954
01:12:04,470 --> 01:12:06,267
Pull yourself together, man.

955
01:12:06,338 --> 01:12:07,828
Nobody told me!

956
01:12:08,774 --> 01:12:11,038
You sold all our stock?

957
01:12:11,477 --> 01:12:13,069
We dumped the whole load.

958
01:12:13,145 --> 01:12:15,511
I had 20,000 shares!

959
01:12:16,248 --> 01:12:17,943
I'd be a millionaire now!

960
01:12:18,050 --> 01:12:20,109
Sure. We'd all be millionaires.

961
01:12:20,819 --> 01:12:22,912
There's no point in looking back.

962
01:12:23,655 --> 01:12:27,591
At the time, Stillson thought that dumping
our position would panic the market...

963
01:12:27,659 --> 01:12:29,650
...further depress the stock.

964
01:12:29,928 --> 01:12:33,455
Then we could buy it back and more,
of course, once it got cheap.

965
01:12:33,532 --> 01:12:34,499
Cheap?

966
01:12:34,933 --> 01:12:36,833
It's never been more valuable!

967
01:12:38,771 --> 01:12:40,033
And I'm ruined.

968
01:12:40,773 --> 01:12:41,762
Ruined!

969
01:12:49,048 --> 01:12:52,279
I'm getting off this merry-go-round!

970
01:13:02,394 --> 01:13:03,520
Plexiglass.

971
01:13:04,129 --> 01:13:05,892
Had it installed last week.

972
01:13:19,812 --> 01:13:21,507
So, the kid caught a wave.

973
01:13:23,215 --> 01:13:26,707
Right now, he and his dingus are on top.

974
01:13:27,319 --> 01:13:29,048
Well, this too shall pass.

975
01:13:29,988 --> 01:13:33,116
Myrtle J. Mussburger
did not raise her boy to go...

976
01:13:33,659 --> 01:13:36,389
...knock-kneed at the first sign of adversity.

977
01:13:36,462 --> 01:13:39,363
I say, we made this chump,
we can break him!

978
01:13:40,232 --> 01:13:43,030
I say, the higher he climbs,
the harder he drops!

979
01:13:44,903 --> 01:13:45,995
I say, yes...

980
01:13:46,905 --> 01:13:48,600
...the kid has a future...

981
01:13:50,008 --> 01:13:51,270
...and in it...

982
01:13:52,244 --> 01:13:54,269
...I see shame, dishonor...

983
01:13:54,913 --> 01:13:56,710
...ignominy, disgrace.

984
01:14:00,686 --> 01:14:02,916
The music plays, the wheel turns...

985
01:14:04,189 --> 01:14:06,214
...and our spin ain't over yet.

986
01:14:30,949 --> 01:14:32,940
For Pete's sakes, Norville!

987
01:14:33,318 --> 01:14:35,218
Where have you been hiding?

988
01:14:35,387 --> 01:14:38,720
Do you know what those nincompoops
in the boardroom are doing?

989
01:14:38,790 --> 01:14:40,417
I wouldn't call them nincompoops.

990
01:14:40,492 --> 01:14:42,983
They're going to discharge 8%
of the workforce here!

991
01:14:43,061 --> 01:14:46,030
In New York City alone,
that means 1,800 people out of work!

992
01:14:46,098 --> 01:14:48,498
People with wives, children and families!

993
01:14:48,800 --> 01:14:50,995
We're pruning away
some of the dead wood.

994
01:14:51,069 --> 01:14:53,128
You mean you know about this?

995
01:14:53,205 --> 01:14:54,763
Know about it? Sure.

996
01:14:54,840 --> 01:14:58,003
You think the board would do anything
without my authorization?

997
01:14:58,076 --> 01:14:59,566
It was my idea.

998
01:14:59,611 --> 01:15:00,942
-Your--
-Sure it was.

999
01:15:01,013 --> 01:15:03,948
We're in a period of transition.
Things have slowed down.

1000
01:15:04,016 --> 01:15:06,814
You're being awfully kind to yourself,
Norville Barnes.

1001
01:15:06,885 --> 01:15:10,321
You've slowed down, sitting up here
not doing a lick of work.

1002
01:15:10,856 --> 01:15:15,759
You haven't come up with an idea since
the Hoop and the reason is plain to see!

1003
01:15:15,827 --> 01:15:18,352
You've forgotten what made your ideas
exciting to you.

1004
01:15:18,430 --> 01:15:20,796
It wasn't for the fame and wealth....

1005
01:15:20,899 --> 01:15:24,733
Would you get out of here?
You too, sisters, move it. Out!

1006
01:15:26,972 --> 01:15:30,135
I've been watching you, even though
you've been trying to avoid me.

1007
01:15:30,309 --> 01:15:31,003
Shut up!

1008
01:15:31,076 --> 01:15:33,374
Don't think I haven't noticed
how you've changed.

1009
01:15:33,445 --> 01:15:35,242
I used to think you were a swell guy.

1010
01:15:35,314 --> 01:15:37,373
To be honest,
I thought you were an imbecile.

1011
01:15:37,783 --> 01:15:38,579
Shut up!

1012
01:15:38,650 --> 01:15:42,245
Then I figured out you were a swell guy.
A little slow maybe, but a swell guy.

1013
01:15:42,321 --> 01:15:45,779
Maybe you're not so slow
but you're not so swell either.

1014
01:15:45,857 --> 01:15:48,087
Looks like you're an imbecile, after all.
Shut up!

1015
01:15:48,794 --> 01:15:52,230
You haven't talked to me for a week
and now I'm going to say my piece.

1016
01:15:52,297 --> 01:15:54,322
Look, I've never been...

1017
01:15:55,300 --> 01:15:57,894
...dumped by a fella before,
and that hurts...

1018
01:15:58,270 --> 01:16:01,137
...but what really hurts is watching you
out-run your soul!

1019
01:16:01,206 --> 01:16:03,606
Chasing after money and ease
and the respect of a board...

1020
01:16:03,675 --> 01:16:06,041
...that wouldn't give you the time of day...

1021
01:16:06,111 --> 01:16:07,078
...if you....

1022
01:16:07,679 --> 01:16:09,078
Worked in a watch factory?

1023
01:16:10,649 --> 01:16:12,014
Shut up! Exactly.

1024
01:16:13,285 --> 01:16:16,812
Norville, don't you remember
how you used to feel about the Hoop?

1025
01:16:17,389 --> 01:16:20,984
You told me you'd bring a smile
to the hips of everyone in America...

1026
01:16:21,059 --> 01:16:23,027
...regardless of race, creed or color.

1027
01:16:23,095 --> 01:16:26,724
Finally, there'd be a thingamajig
that would bring everyone together...

1028
01:16:26,798 --> 01:16:29,130
...even if it kept them apart spatially.

1029
01:16:29,568 --> 01:16:30,660
"You know...

1030
01:16:31,169 --> 01:16:32,193
"...for kids."

1031
01:16:33,071 --> 01:16:34,060
Your words...

1032
01:16:35,173 --> 01:16:36,299
...not mine.

1033
01:16:37,676 --> 01:16:39,337
I used to love Norville Barnes.

1034
01:16:40,412 --> 01:16:41,777
Yes, love him...

1035
01:16:42,514 --> 01:16:46,541
...when he was just a swell kid
with hot ideas who was in over his head.

1036
01:16:47,286 --> 01:16:49,584
Now your head's too big to be in over!

1037
01:16:49,721 --> 01:16:51,621
Consider this my resignation.

1038
01:16:52,924 --> 01:16:54,414
Effective immediately!

1039
01:18:14,439 --> 01:18:16,236
Buddy, buddy.

1040
01:18:17,142 --> 01:18:18,166
Buddy.

1041
01:18:19,111 --> 01:18:20,442
Oh, buddy.

1042
01:18:30,222 --> 01:18:31,553
Buddy. You busy?

1043
01:18:33,392 --> 01:18:36,850
Looks like you nodded off there, buddy.
Say, you got a minute?

1044
01:18:40,465 --> 01:18:41,830
Is this important?

1045
01:18:41,900 --> 01:18:45,199
I think so. It's this little idea
I've been working on.

1046
01:18:45,270 --> 01:18:47,966
You see, I don't intend
to be an elevator boy forever.

1047
01:18:48,039 --> 01:18:49,631
Take a look at this sweet baby!

1048
01:18:49,708 --> 01:18:52,142
Get it? Incredibly convenient, isn't it?

1049
01:18:52,244 --> 01:18:53,802
You know, for drinks?

1050
01:18:54,012 --> 01:18:57,971
This is how it works. It's got these ridges
on the side that give it its whammy.

1051
01:18:58,083 --> 01:19:01,746
You don't have to drink like this.
You can drink like this.

1052
01:19:01,853 --> 01:19:04,151
I call it the "Buzz-Sucker."
You get it, buddy?

1053
01:19:04,222 --> 01:19:08,090
People are dying for this and
we won't have to charge an arm and a leg.

1054
01:19:08,160 --> 01:19:09,388
Wait a minute.

1055
01:19:24,743 --> 01:19:25,732
This...

1056
01:19:28,847 --> 01:19:30,007
...is worthless!

1057
01:19:30,315 --> 01:19:31,407
But, buddy!

1058
01:19:31,750 --> 01:19:34,685
This is the most idiotic thing
I've ever seen in my life.

1059
01:19:34,753 --> 01:19:37,085
Nobody wants a hair-brained product
like this.

1060
01:19:37,155 --> 01:19:38,281
You see, Buzz...

1061
01:19:38,356 --> 01:19:40,449
...it lacks the creative spark...

1062
01:19:40,792 --> 01:19:43,818
...the unalloyed genius
that made something like, say...

1063
01:19:44,663 --> 01:19:46,358
...the Hula Hoop such a success.

1064
01:19:46,431 --> 01:19:48,922
How dare you barge in here
and take up my valuable time!

1065
01:19:48,967 --> 01:19:50,366
I've got a company to run!

1066
01:19:52,704 --> 01:19:55,605
I can't have every deadbeat
on the payroll pestering me...

1067
01:19:55,674 --> 01:19:57,403
...with their idiotic brainwaves.

1068
01:19:57,476 --> 01:19:58,704
I'm sorry, buddy.

1069
01:19:58,777 --> 01:20:00,005
An example must be made!

1070
01:20:00,479 --> 01:20:01,912
What do you mean?

1071
01:20:03,048 --> 01:20:04,208
You're fired!

1072
01:20:04,950 --> 01:20:07,043
Is that plain enough for you?

1073
01:20:12,390 --> 01:20:13,789
Oh, buddy!

1074
01:20:14,559 --> 01:20:16,220
And don't call me "buddy"!

1075
01:20:16,995 --> 01:20:21,056
Oh, please, sir! This job running
the elevator, it's all I got!

1076
01:20:21,500 --> 01:20:23,559
It's okay if you don't like the Buzz-Sucker!

1077
01:20:23,635 --> 01:20:26,433
Just let me keep my job,
I'm praying to you!

1078
01:20:27,305 --> 01:20:28,636
Get out of my office!

1079
01:20:29,140 --> 01:20:30,437
Get up! Up!

1080
01:20:31,576 --> 01:20:34,136
We don't crawl here
at Hudsucker lndustries!

1081
01:20:35,814 --> 01:20:37,111
I'm sorry, sir!

1082
01:20:37,282 --> 01:20:38,442
I'm sorry!

1083
01:20:52,931 --> 01:20:54,421
Thank you, Aloysius.

1084
01:20:59,504 --> 01:21:00,664
This is...

1085
01:21:02,507 --> 01:21:03,531
...useful.

1086
01:21:21,660 --> 01:21:25,926
I'm sorry I'm late, Sid. That back nine
at Riverdale's really murder.

1087
01:21:27,198 --> 01:21:30,099
It's a tough course. A real lollapalooza.

1088
01:21:31,636 --> 01:21:32,864
Sit down, son.

1089
01:21:36,241 --> 01:21:40,337
I thought the boardroom would be
a swell place to chat undisturbed.

1090
01:21:41,479 --> 01:21:44,846
Seems we've got some security problems
here at the Hud.

1091
01:21:45,984 --> 01:21:46,882
You don't say.

1092
01:21:46,952 --> 01:21:51,286
Ordinarily, I wouldn't bother you with it,
but this is embarrassing.

1093
01:21:52,657 --> 01:21:54,818
It concerns you directly.

1094
01:21:55,160 --> 01:21:57,720
-How's that?
-It's not serious in itself.

1095
01:21:58,396 --> 01:22:01,160
Some elevator boy that you'd fired
came to me...

1096
01:22:01,766 --> 01:22:05,566
...claiming that you'd stolen
the idea for the dingus.

1097
01:22:05,904 --> 01:22:07,599
You'd stolen it from him.

1098
01:22:10,742 --> 01:22:13,176
-Maybe I was a little rough on him--
-Forget it.

1099
01:22:13,244 --> 01:22:16,873
You don't have to explain to me.
He's a little person. He's nothing.

1100
01:22:16,948 --> 01:22:18,506
Fire whoever you want.

1101
01:22:20,518 --> 01:22:22,315
No, the problem is...

1102
01:22:22,954 --> 01:22:24,285
...who you hired.

1103
01:22:24,756 --> 01:22:25,848
That dame.

1104
01:22:26,291 --> 01:22:27,883
A spy, as it turns out.

1105
01:22:28,827 --> 01:22:31,591
She must have gotten
to that elevator schnook...

1106
01:22:32,364 --> 01:22:34,491
...and her paper is going to town.

1107
01:22:35,600 --> 01:22:40,003
Sure, sure, we tried to kill the story,
but the Argus won't play ball.

1108
01:22:41,873 --> 01:22:45,036
The problem the board will have is
you hired this woman...

1109
01:22:45,410 --> 01:22:47,105
...and you kept her on...

1110
01:22:47,445 --> 01:22:49,970
...while she was making
a chump out of you.

1111
01:22:50,548 --> 01:22:52,311
Serious error in judgement.

1112
01:22:53,885 --> 01:22:55,409
Business is war, kid.

1113
01:22:56,554 --> 01:22:59,045
Take no prisoners, give no second chances.

1114
01:23:02,894 --> 01:23:05,385
When the board meets after New Year's...

1115
01:23:05,530 --> 01:23:07,020
...your position....

1116
01:23:09,734 --> 01:23:11,497
Looks like you're finished.

1117
01:23:12,237 --> 01:23:13,295
Washed up.

1118
01:23:19,077 --> 01:23:21,045
Fourteenth hole at Riverdale...

1119
01:23:21,413 --> 01:23:22,971
...some use a mashie...

1120
01:23:23,214 --> 01:23:24,704
...some use a niblick.

1121
01:23:25,684 --> 01:23:26,742
Niblick.

1122
01:23:27,318 --> 01:23:29,582
You get more loft, more backspin.

1123
01:23:34,492 --> 01:23:35,618
That dame...

1124
01:23:37,095 --> 01:23:39,461
...she got your throat pretty well slit.

1125
01:23:40,598 --> 01:23:42,589
When you're dead, you stay dead.

1126
01:23:43,468 --> 01:23:45,959
You don't believe me,
ask Waring Hudsucker.

1127
01:23:48,239 --> 01:23:49,570
Tough luck, kid.

1128
01:23:50,241 --> 01:23:51,936
You had a short climb up.

1129
01:23:53,078 --> 01:23:54,602
It's a long way down.

1130
01:24:07,325 --> 01:24:10,886
-You can't print that!
-We are! She hits the streets tonight.

1131
01:24:11,863 --> 01:24:13,592
And she's dynamite!

1132
01:24:13,665 --> 01:24:17,795
But it's the bunk! Norville showed me his
design for the whatsit the day I met him.

1133
01:24:17,869 --> 01:24:20,667
Buzz couldn't have invented it.
Look at him, he's an imbecile.

1134
01:24:20,739 --> 01:24:24,675
Aren't you a broken record?
Gunderson did design it. He's a prodigy.

1135
01:24:24,809 --> 01:24:27,243
-Says who?
-You're not the only one with sources.

1136
01:24:27,312 --> 01:24:29,940
Smith has a senior source
on the Hud Board. Very senior.

1137
01:24:30,181 --> 01:24:32,411
I bet his initials are Sidney J. Mussburger.

1138
01:24:33,151 --> 01:24:35,813
You lost it. You gone soft,
by the looks of it.

1139
01:24:35,887 --> 01:24:37,479
Soft on the dummy from Dubuque.

1140
01:24:38,523 --> 01:24:39,854
-Muncie.
-Whatever!

1141
01:24:39,924 --> 01:24:43,826
This story's hot and you're no longer
on top of it. It's the scoop of the century!

1142
01:24:43,895 --> 01:24:46,090
The other papers won't have this
till tomorrow!

1143
01:24:46,164 --> 01:24:50,066
Allemeinisher Zeitung, Le Figaro
will be choking on our dust come morning.

1144
01:24:50,135 --> 01:24:53,571
You're fools, both of you!
You're being used, don't you see?

1145
01:24:53,905 --> 01:24:56,840
Take a break. You worked hard on this.
You broke it for us.

1146
01:24:56,908 --> 01:24:59,342
But it's passed you by
and Smith's taking up the slack.

1147
01:25:01,613 --> 01:25:02,944
You want slack...

1148
01:25:03,581 --> 01:25:04,912
...I'll give you slack!

1149
01:25:04,983 --> 01:25:09,420
You're not putting me out to pasture!
I quit! Consider this my resignation!

1150
01:25:10,688 --> 01:25:12,280
Effective immediately!

1151
01:25:15,026 --> 01:25:16,015
Soft.

1152
01:25:25,403 --> 01:25:26,893
So, tell me...

1153
01:25:27,372 --> 01:25:30,000
...why do you feel this woman
betrayed you?

1154
01:25:32,377 --> 01:25:33,935
What's the difference?

1155
01:25:34,012 --> 01:25:36,776
The whole world, it seems, is against you?

1156
01:25:36,881 --> 01:25:38,143
I don't know.

1157
01:25:38,249 --> 01:25:40,012
Und the elevator boy...

1158
01:25:40,118 --> 01:25:43,281
...Buzz, he too works against you?

1159
01:25:45,557 --> 01:25:46,581
Classic.

1160
01:25:46,958 --> 01:25:50,223
Patient displayed listlessness, apathy,
gloomy indifference...

1161
01:25:50,295 --> 01:25:52,126
...und was blue und mopey.

1162
01:25:52,630 --> 01:25:56,259
When asked what the Rorschach stains
represented, patient replied:

1163
01:25:56,367 --> 01:26:00,428
"Nothing much. I don't know.
Just a blotch. Sure beats me."

1164
01:26:01,206 --> 01:26:04,437
Patient shows no ambition,
no get-up-and-go, no vim.

1165
01:26:05,143 --> 01:26:07,441
He is riding the grand loopen-ze-loop...

1166
01:26:07,812 --> 01:26:10,781
...that goes from the height
of delusional gaiety...

1167
01:26:10,849 --> 01:26:12,646
...to the trough of despair.

1168
01:26:13,184 --> 01:26:15,982
He is now near,
but not yet at his lowest point.

1169
01:26:16,387 --> 01:26:20,824
When he reaches bottom, he may erupt
und pose a danger to himself...

1170
01:26:21,059 --> 01:26:22,048
...and others.

1171
01:26:22,260 --> 01:26:24,387
Diagnosis, Dr. Bromfenbrenner?

1172
01:26:24,629 --> 01:26:27,621
Patient is eine manic-depressive paranoid,
type B...

1173
01:26:27,799 --> 01:26:29,596
...with acute schizoid tendencies.

1174
01:26:29,968 --> 01:26:31,731
So, patient is...?

1175
01:26:33,404 --> 01:26:34,462
Precisely.

1176
01:26:35,139 --> 01:26:36,163
Nuts!

1177
01:26:36,641 --> 01:26:37,869
Prescription?

1178
01:26:38,042 --> 01:26:40,010
Three things: Commitment...

1179
01:26:40,612 --> 01:26:42,910
...electroconvulsive therapy...

1180
01:26:43,014 --> 01:26:45,505
...maintenance in eine secure facility.

1181
01:27:01,299 --> 01:27:03,494
Yeah, he's a tall guy. A real mess.

1182
01:27:05,303 --> 01:27:08,864
Look, you better get down here.
He says he's a friend of yours.

1183
01:27:09,040 --> 01:27:11,941
He didn't say.
But, man, is he from Squaresville.

1184
01:27:20,551 --> 01:27:21,916
I want a martini!

1185
01:27:22,553 --> 01:27:24,953
It's New Year's Eve. I deserve a martini.

1186
01:27:25,356 --> 01:27:27,153
It's like I've been telling you--

1187
01:27:27,225 --> 01:27:29,386
I thought you served misfits here!

1188
01:27:29,494 --> 01:27:32,019
That's a roger. But we don't sell alcohol.

1189
01:27:32,497 --> 01:27:34,988
What kind of bar doesn't serve martinis?

1190
01:27:35,199 --> 01:27:38,726
It's a juice-and-coffee bar, man,
like I've been telling you.

1191
01:27:38,970 --> 01:27:41,029
Right. So, I want...

1192
01:27:42,407 --> 01:27:43,601
...a martini.

1193
01:27:44,342 --> 01:27:47,402
I've had a martini in every bar
on the way down here.

1194
01:27:48,012 --> 01:27:50,037
Martinis are for squares, man.

1195
01:27:52,050 --> 01:27:54,848
What'd you call me, you beatnik son of a--

1196
01:28:00,959 --> 01:28:02,358
Look who's here:

1197
01:28:02,493 --> 01:28:03,790
Amy Archer...

1198
01:28:04,062 --> 01:28:05,723
...Prizeter Pule winner.

1199
01:28:06,397 --> 01:28:08,661
Looking for a nitwit to buy you lunch?

1200
01:28:09,600 --> 01:28:11,864
-Bar fella, I'd like...
-I'm sorry.

1201
01:28:12,570 --> 01:28:13,969
...a martini, please.

1202
01:28:14,038 --> 01:28:16,438
I tried to tell you so many times, l....

1203
01:28:17,875 --> 01:28:19,308
It's hard to admit...

1204
01:28:19,377 --> 01:28:21,208
...when you've been wrong.

1205
01:28:21,813 --> 01:28:23,303
If you could just...

1206
01:28:23,715 --> 01:28:25,546
...find it in your heart...

1207
01:28:26,150 --> 01:28:28,050
...to give me another chance.

1208
01:28:30,488 --> 01:28:32,979
"You take no prisoners,
give no second chances."

1209
01:28:33,057 --> 01:28:35,924
Please, Norville!
Please give me one more chance!

1210
01:28:36,661 --> 01:28:37,992
And yourself, too!

1211
01:28:38,162 --> 01:28:39,993
We both deserve one.

1212
01:28:40,231 --> 01:28:43,860
Just give us a second chance.
Together we can fight this thing.

1213
01:28:44,002 --> 01:28:48,132
I know the last story was a lie
and we can prove it. Release a statement!

1214
01:28:48,206 --> 01:28:51,175
-I can help you write it!
-What's the difference?

1215
01:28:51,876 --> 01:28:53,241
I'm all washed up.

1216
01:28:54,679 --> 01:28:55,668
Extinct.

1217
01:28:56,180 --> 01:28:58,273
Homo sapiens sapicus.

1218
01:29:01,219 --> 01:29:03,312
That just about does it.

1219
01:29:04,288 --> 01:29:07,621
I've seen Norville Barnes,
the young man in a big hurry...

1220
01:29:08,092 --> 01:29:11,323
...and I've seen Norville Barnes,
the self-important heel.

1221
01:29:11,662 --> 01:29:14,597
But I've never seen Norville Barnes,
the quitter...

1222
01:29:15,400 --> 01:29:16,992
...and I don't like it.

1223
01:29:18,770 --> 01:29:20,260
"Fight on

1224
01:29:20,938 --> 01:29:23,805
"Fight on, dear old Muncie

1225
01:29:25,443 --> 01:29:28,606
"Fight on
Hoist the gold and blue

1226
01:29:30,081 --> 01:29:33,107
"You'll be tattered, torn and hurting

1227
01:29:34,018 --> 01:29:37,476
"Once the Munce is done with you

1228
01:29:40,024 --> 01:29:41,616
"Go...

1229
01:29:41,726 --> 01:29:42,852
"...Eagles! "

1230
01:29:45,263 --> 01:29:48,357
You can't surrender, Norville! Remember:

1231
01:29:49,067 --> 01:29:50,500
"Fight on

1232
01:29:50,768 --> 01:29:52,201
"Fight on

1233
01:29:52,303 --> 01:29:54,703
"Dear old Muncie

1234
01:29:55,239 --> 01:29:56,604
"Fight on

1235
01:29:56,674 --> 01:30:00,201
"Hoist the gold and blue

1236
01:30:01,312 --> 01:30:03,473
"You'll be tattered, torn...

1237
01:30:03,548 --> 01:30:05,539
"...and hurting...."

1238
01:30:07,351 --> 01:30:08,613
You lied to me.

1239
01:30:09,387 --> 01:30:11,048
How could you lie to me?

1240
01:30:13,191 --> 01:30:14,180
You...

1241
01:30:14,892 --> 01:30:16,223
...a Muncie girl.

1242
01:30:18,162 --> 01:30:19,993
But, Norville, l--

1243
01:30:20,898 --> 01:30:22,923
"When you're dead, you stay dead!"

1244
01:30:23,534 --> 01:30:24,626
Just ask...

1245
01:30:24,702 --> 01:30:26,431
...Waring Hudsucker!

1246
01:30:33,711 --> 01:30:35,201
Extra, extra!

1247
01:30:35,313 --> 01:30:37,110
New Year's Eve edition!

1248
01:30:37,181 --> 01:30:39,615
Barnes' brain caught red-handed!

1249
01:30:39,750 --> 01:30:41,183
Ideas ersatz!

1250
01:30:41,652 --> 01:30:44,348
Man from Muncie a moron after all!

1251
01:30:44,722 --> 01:30:46,849
Read all about it!

1252
01:30:47,024 --> 01:30:51,358
New Year's Eve edition!
Man from Muncie a moron after all!

1253
01:30:51,529 --> 01:30:53,759
You're not so slow, but you're not so swell.

1254
01:30:53,831 --> 01:30:56,527
And it looks like you're an imbecile
after all.

1255
01:30:56,968 --> 01:30:59,334
But your friends called you "dope?"

1256
01:30:59,403 --> 01:31:01,633
"Dipstick?" "Lamebrain?" "Schmo?"

1257
01:31:01,706 --> 01:31:04,869
Please, buddy, running the elevator,
it's all I got.

1258
01:31:04,942 --> 01:31:07,069
Norville, you let me down.

1259
01:31:07,145 --> 01:31:11,639
You let Mrs. Eisenhower down.
You let the American people down.

1260
01:31:11,716 --> 01:31:14,276
And when you're dead, you stay dead.

1261
01:31:17,688 --> 01:31:19,883
The kid is screwy, it's official.

1262
01:31:21,359 --> 01:31:24,260
The barred-window boys
are out looking for him now.

1263
01:31:24,762 --> 01:31:26,559
We'll see how Wall Street likes the news...

1264
01:31:26,631 --> 01:31:30,032
...that the president of Hudsucker
is heading for the booby hatch.

1265
01:31:31,736 --> 01:31:34,398
When Doc Bromfenbrenner gets through
with him...

1266
01:31:34,906 --> 01:31:36,840
...he'll need diapers and a dribble cup.

1267
01:31:39,277 --> 01:31:40,608
If that's all....

1268
01:31:40,912 --> 01:31:42,641
Long live the Hud!

1269
01:31:52,623 --> 01:31:53,954
Watch where you're--

1270
01:31:54,025 --> 01:31:55,652
Hiya, buddy!

1271
01:31:56,561 --> 01:31:58,756
Out on the town? Guess what?

1272
01:31:58,829 --> 01:32:01,696
Mr.... Sid says I can have my old job back!

1273
01:32:01,766 --> 01:32:03,700
I deserve a second chance, he says.

1274
01:32:03,935 --> 01:32:04,731
He did?

1275
01:32:04,802 --> 01:32:07,236
Turns out he's not such a bad guy after all.

1276
01:32:07,805 --> 01:32:09,295
That's wonderful.

1277
01:32:09,774 --> 01:32:13,369
He said you stole that swell hoop idea
from me. What gives?

1278
01:32:13,544 --> 01:32:14,806
I would never--

1279
01:32:14,879 --> 01:32:16,710
Gee, that was a swell idea.

1280
01:32:17,548 --> 01:32:19,311
And Sid says you stoled it!

1281
01:32:19,784 --> 01:32:22,275
What are you waiting for? Pop him one!

1282
01:32:32,797 --> 01:32:34,526
He's that big-shot faker!

1283
01:32:34,599 --> 01:32:36,430
That Wall Street fraud!

1284
01:32:36,534 --> 01:32:38,365
Nuttier than a fruitcake!

1285
01:32:39,737 --> 01:32:41,398
Somebody call the cops!

1286
01:33:13,070 --> 01:33:15,265
Ring out the old, ring in the new!

1287
01:37:57,721 --> 01:38:00,383
Strictly speaking, I'm never supposed
to do this...

1288
01:38:00,457 --> 01:38:02,448
...but have you got a better idea?

1289
01:39:10,594 --> 01:39:12,960
Love that tune. How you doing, kid?

1290
01:39:14,031 --> 01:39:15,362
Mr. Hudsucker?

1291
01:39:16,567 --> 01:39:19,365
How do you like that thing?
They're all wearing them upstairs.

1292
01:39:19,436 --> 01:39:20,528
It's a fad.

1293
01:39:20,771 --> 01:39:21,829
Anyway...

1294
01:39:22,306 --> 01:39:23,796
...I see you've been having some...

1295
01:39:23,874 --> 01:39:25,466
...problems with the board.

1296
01:39:25,609 --> 01:39:28,169
I guess Sidney's been putting
the screws to you, Norman.

1297
01:39:28,646 --> 01:39:29,874
Norville.

1298
01:39:30,247 --> 01:39:33,478
Say what you like about his ethics,
he's a balls-to-the-wall businessman.

1299
01:39:33,550 --> 01:39:36,849
Beat you any way he can.
Straight for the jugular. Very effective.

1300
01:39:36,920 --> 01:39:40,151
Any particular reason you didn't give him
my blue letter?

1301
01:39:40,257 --> 01:39:43,818
Norman, just a dying man's last words
and wishes, no big deal.

1302
01:39:45,229 --> 01:39:46,787
I must've mislaid it.

1303
01:39:46,864 --> 01:39:49,799
It's in your apron pocket,
right where you left it.

1304
01:39:50,267 --> 01:39:51,256
Imbecile.

1305
01:39:51,402 --> 01:39:54,428
Failure to deliver a blue letter
is grounds for dismissal.

1306
01:39:56,006 --> 01:39:59,066
It's New Year's. I'm not going to add
to your woes.

1307
01:39:59,176 --> 01:40:01,610
Want to read it?
You might learn something.

1308
01:40:02,046 --> 01:40:04,606
Might keep you from jumping
out of any more windows.

1309
01:40:10,521 --> 01:40:13,684
"Blue letter from the desk
of Waring Hudsucker...

1310
01:40:14,391 --> 01:40:17,258
"...to Sidney J. Mussburger,
regarding my demise.

1311
01:40:17,461 --> 01:40:18,553
"Dear Sid:

1312
01:40:18,629 --> 01:40:22,224
"By the time you read this, I will have
joined the organization upstairs...

1313
01:40:22,299 --> 01:40:25,996
"...an exciting new beginning.
I will retain fond--"

1314
01:40:26,103 --> 01:40:27,035
Memories.

1315
01:40:27,104 --> 01:40:29,368
"Of the years you and I have spent--"

1316
01:40:30,274 --> 01:40:33,710
Standard resignation boilerplate.
Go down to the second paragraph.

1317
01:40:39,550 --> 01:40:41,814
"You will no doubt be wondering
why I've decided...

1318
01:40:41,885 --> 01:40:44,752
"...to end my tenure both at Hudsucker
and here on earth.

1319
01:40:45,289 --> 01:40:47,883
"From the standpoint of our balance sheet
and financials...

1320
01:40:47,958 --> 01:40:49,755
"...sure, we're doing fine.

1321
01:40:49,860 --> 01:40:52,829
"But in my personal life,
I have made grave errors.

1322
01:40:53,263 --> 01:40:55,527
"l let my success become my identity.

1323
01:40:55,966 --> 01:40:58,196
"l have foolishly played the great man...

1324
01:40:58,268 --> 01:41:01,704
"...and watched my life become more
and more empty as a result.

1325
01:41:02,039 --> 01:41:04,007
"My vanity drove away she...

1326
01:41:04,808 --> 01:41:06,537
"...who could've saved me.

1327
01:41:07,111 --> 01:41:10,012
"Yes, I loved a woman once, Sid,
as you well know.

1328
01:41:10,647 --> 01:41:12,444
"A beautiful, vibrant lady...

1329
01:41:12,516 --> 01:41:16,577
"...and angel who, in her wisdom,
saw fit to choose you instead of l."

1330
01:41:23,994 --> 01:41:25,256
Skip this part.

1331
01:41:27,664 --> 01:41:29,598
Next page. Next page!

1332
01:41:40,110 --> 01:41:42,874
"This brings me to our company, Sid,
and its future.

1333
01:41:42,946 --> 01:41:46,177
"Our next president must have the liberty
I have had as owner...

1334
01:41:46,250 --> 01:41:48,184
"...to experiment and even fall..."

1335
01:41:48,252 --> 01:41:48,946
Fail.

1336
01:41:49,019 --> 01:41:52,853
"...without fear of the whims
of the stockholders or an impatient board.

1337
01:41:53,423 --> 01:41:56,187
-"The new president must be free to fall..."
-Fail!

1338
01:41:56,260 --> 01:41:57,693
"...and learn to fail..."

1339
01:41:57,761 --> 01:41:58,420
Fall!

1340
01:41:58,495 --> 01:42:00,656
"...and rise again by applying...

1341
01:42:00,731 --> 01:42:02,130
"...what he has learned.

1342
01:42:02,199 --> 01:42:03,564
"Such is business.

1343
01:42:04,134 --> 01:42:05,431
"Such is life.

1344
01:42:06,570 --> 01:42:08,367
"Accordingly, I hereby bequeath...

1345
01:42:08,438 --> 01:42:11,100
"...all of my shares in Hudsucker lndustry...

1346
01:42:11,175 --> 01:42:14,042
"...to whomever you
and the board shall elect...

1347
01:42:14,411 --> 01:42:16,379
"...to succeed me as president.

1348
01:42:17,047 --> 01:42:18,844
"l assume this will be you.

1349
01:42:18,949 --> 01:42:22,680
"lf not, if the board chooses someone else
to be president...

1350
01:42:22,753 --> 01:42:23,845
"...then, then...."

1351
01:42:23,921 --> 01:42:25,411
Tough titty toenails!

1352
01:42:27,858 --> 01:42:29,450
That'll show the bastard!

1353
01:42:38,502 --> 01:42:39,560
Go ahead.

1354
01:42:39,636 --> 01:42:42,036
"l urge you to work
with the new president...

1355
01:42:42,105 --> 01:42:44,505
"...and to remind him when he needs
to be reminded...

1356
01:42:44,575 --> 01:42:47,100
"...that failure should never lead
to despair.

1357
01:42:48,879 --> 01:42:51,040
"Despair looks only to the past...

1358
01:42:51,315 --> 01:42:52,612
"...in business...

1359
01:42:55,419 --> 01:42:56,750
"...and in love."

1360
01:42:57,321 --> 01:42:58,982
The future is now.

1361
01:43:00,023 --> 01:43:01,217
"The future is now.

1362
01:43:02,926 --> 01:43:04,894
"When our future president needs it...

1363
01:43:05,662 --> 01:43:06,651
"...Waring Hudsucker...

1364
01:43:07,965 --> 01:43:09,455
"...hereby bequeaths him...

1365
01:43:10,868 --> 01:43:12,460
"...his second chance."

1366
01:43:44,234 --> 01:43:46,725
Deliver that letter in the morning!

1367
01:44:47,197 --> 01:44:49,961
And so began 1959.

1368
01:44:50,834 --> 01:44:52,165
The New Year.

1369
01:44:52,602 --> 01:44:57,039
When he learned that Norville owned
the company, Sidney was upset at first.

1370
01:44:57,507 --> 01:45:00,305
It's a good thing Doc Bromfenbrenner
was there...

1371
01:45:01,345 --> 01:45:04,746
...because he was able to keep Sidney
from harming himself.

1372
01:45:05,182 --> 01:45:09,209
He prescribed a long rest in the sana....
In the sanatory....

1373
01:45:09,553 --> 01:45:10,918
In the booby hatch.

1374
01:45:12,089 --> 01:45:13,420
Now, Norville...

1375
01:45:14,091 --> 01:45:17,117
...he went on and ruled
with wisdom and compassion...

1376
01:45:17,828 --> 01:45:21,127
...and started dreaming up
them exciting new ideas again.

1377
01:45:21,765 --> 01:45:23,198
You know, for kids.

1378
01:45:23,400 --> 01:45:26,233
I had the boys down at R&D
throw together this prototype...

1379
01:45:26,303 --> 01:45:28,203
...so our discussion could have focus...

1380
01:45:28,271 --> 01:45:31,104
...and to give you gentlemen of the board
a firsthand look.

1381
01:45:36,546 --> 01:45:40,880
That's the story of how Norville Barnes
climbed way up...

1382
01:45:40,984 --> 01:45:43,817
...to the 44th floor
of the Hudsucker building...

1383
01:45:44,554 --> 01:45:48,547
...and then fell all the way down,
but didn't quite squish himself.

1384
01:45:49,593 --> 01:45:53,256
You know, they say there was a man
who jumped from the 45th floor.

1385
01:45:54,097 --> 01:45:55,826
But that's another story.

